<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak, Albright Hold Talks Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
held talks again with visiting U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright Tuesday night to exchange their opinions on how to push
forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
There is no news conference about the outcome of the meeting,
which was their second in less than 24 hours to narrow the
difference between Israel and the Palestinians in reaching a
framework agreement on final-status issues.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel Radio quoted Barak as saying that he has
determination to seize the moment of truth to reach a final peace
with the Palestinians. He did not elaborate further.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived in the Middle East region on Monday, had
held talks with Barak Monday evening and Tuesday afternoon. Earlier
Tuesday, she also met Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy respectively.
</P>
<P>
During her talks with Arafat, the secretary of state managed to
persuade the Palestinian leader to accept an arrangement, in which
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will be sent back to the
Washington area early next week and resume their works on a final
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the meeting date between Arafat and U.S. President
Bill Clinton at the White House was also slated for June 14, which
is a move to push forward the peace process further after Clinton's
meeting with Barak in Portugal last week.
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed her hope on Tuesday afternoon after meeting
with Levy that the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations will make
tangible progress on key final-status issues, such as the fate of
Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees, border,
security and water, with full-speed after the resumption.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians launched their intensive peace talks
in March in the United States and moved the talks back to the
region in April.
</P>
<P>
In May, it was revealed that the two sides had opened a secret
channel in Stockholm, capital of Sweden, to speed up the
finalization of the framework agreement. This channel has also been
moved back to the region by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Tuesday night by Barak's office said that the
two side's delegation to next week's Washington round of talks
would be led respectively by Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-
Ami and Ahmed Qurei, Speaker of the Palestinian Legislative
Council.
</P>
<P>
The two negotiators had cooperated in so-called "back-channel"
Stockholm talks in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the proposed three-way summit between Clinton,
Barak and Arafat, the statement said: "Only after the extent of
progress in the deliberations is examined will it be decided
whether to convene a three-way summit."
</P>
<P>
Albright also admitted at the joint news conference with Levy
that the conditions for holding such a Camp David-style summit
between U.S., Israeli and Palestinian leaders are still immature.
</P>
<P>
Clearing the way for such a meeting by the end of June in the
United States is reportedly the major task of Albright's current
Middle East tour.
</P>
<P>
It has been hoped that such a summit will reach a final-status
framework agreement between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the United States, Egypt and Israel met in Camp David
in 1979 and hammered out a treaty, the first between an Arab
country and the Jewish state, to realize peace between the two
Middle East powers.
</P>
<P>
Albright pointed out Tuesday afternoon that She and President
Clinton had "rolled up sleeves" to help the two sides to reach a
peace plan, but the final decision should be made by Israeli and
Palestinians leaders themselves.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to leave Jerusalem for Cairo Wednesday
morning to meet with foreign ministers from Arab countries there,
including Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
