<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Coalition to Be Formed in Days: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
suggested Wednesday night that he will form a new coalition "in a
matter of days", rejecting the possibility of an early election.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israel's Channel One television, Barak stated
that any ministers voting along with the oppositions for an early
election bill in the Knesset earlier Wednesday had "fired
themselves."
</P>
<P>
This means that as a result of their voting against the
government, ministers from three of his ruling partners -- Shas,
National Religious Party (NRP) and Yisrael Ba'aliya -- will be
dismissed soon.
</P>
<P>
These ministers are Labor and Social Affairs Minister Eli
Yishai, Religious Affairs Minister Yitzhak Cohen, Health Minister
Shlomo Benizri, National Infrastructure Minister Eli Suissa, all
from Shas, Construction and Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy, from
NRP, and Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, from Yisrael Ba'aliya.
</P>
<P>
A "formal announcement" would follow Sunday's weekly cabinet
meeting, Barak added, as technically a cabinet meeting is required
for the dismissal of ministers.
</P>
<P>
Barak declined to elaborate on the possible makeup of the new
coalition. But it has been speculated that the secular Shinui,
Democratic List, and Am Ehad will join the coalition since the
Shas, NRP and Yisrael Ba'aliya are leaving.
</P>
<P>
Such a new coalition will hold 52 seats in the 120-member
Knesset, thus depending on the support from 10 Israeli Arab
legislators outside the coalition for its survival.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said that on Sunday, the cabinet will meet
and the "appropriate decisions will be made."
</P>
<P>
Similar or different, the new coalition will tolerate "a minimum
of deal making" and would include a "maximum of action," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
The new government would therefore deal with national and urgent
issues in a more harmonious atmosphere, said Barak.
</P>
<P>
The ultra-Orthodox religious Shas party was demanding more
government funding for its financially ailing educational network
in exchange for its pivotal 17 Knesset members' support for Barak's
peace efforts with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak refused to make concessions under Shas threat to support
the bill against the government, and ordered the cancellation of
negotiations with the party.
</P>
<P>
Barak said in a televised interview Wednesday night that he is
directly authorized by Israeli people to make important political
and social decisions, anybody or any party's trick will not hamper
his determination to make such decisions.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that he will not sign any peace deals with the
Palestinians unless Israel's demands for security guarantee are met
and Israel's national interests guarded.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are currently in talks to
reach a framework agreement in preparation for a final peace accord
by September 13 on final-status issues, such as the fate of
Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees, borders,
security and water.
</P>
<P>
Their negotiation teams, led respectively by Israeli Public
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and Palestinian Legislative
Council Speaker Ahmed Qurei (Abu Ala), will go to Washington and
resume talks there early next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
