<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2030 GMT, Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Two people were killed and 81 others wounded in a 5.9-
magnitude quake which occurred on Tuesday morning in the northern
Turkish province of Cankiri, the Prime Ministry Crisis Management
Centre announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Buildings in the rural areas of Cerkes and Orta towns, the
epicenter of the quake, were heavily damaged while 70 percent of
the buildings in Cankiri city, 100 kilometers northeast of Turkey's
capital Ankara, were slightly damaged except five buildings
demolished, the statement said. (Turkey-Quake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met on Wednesday with
visiting United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
discuss the latest developments in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Cairo earlier in the day during a regional
trip which has taken her to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule
areas. (Egypt-US-Mideast Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Knesset (Parliament) Wednesday passed a
motion proposed by opposition parties to hold early elections in a
preliminary reading, an event that may hamper Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's efforts to push forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The motion, submitted by Knesset member Avigdor Lieberman from
National Union-Yisrael Beiteinu and Silvan Shalom from the major
opposition Likud party, was approved by a vote of 61-48, with 11
Knesset members failing to show up on the occasion. (Israel-Early
Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Syria left the door open for the resumption of the
Syria-Israeli peace negotiations, said Syrian Foreign Minister
Faruk Shareh here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Syria has no objection to the U.S. viewpoint that there are
chances to resume the Syrian-Israeli talks, and is ready to seek
revival of the talks on the return of the Golan Heights, Shareh
told reporters after meeting here with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. (Egypt-Syria-US-Mideast Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak suggested
Wednesday night that he will form a new coalition "in a matter of
days", rejecting the possibility of early elections.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israel's Channel One television, Barak stated
that any ministers voting along with the oppositions for an early-
election bill in the Knesset earlier Wednesday had "fired
themselves." (Israel-Coalition Crisis) 
</P>
</TEXT>
