<HEADLINE> British Envoy in Cyprus to Prepare for Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's envoy on Cyprus Sir David
Hannay on Wednesday started a four-day visit to Cyprus to prepare
the ground for the third round of U.N.-sponsored talks on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Larnaca airport on Cyprus' southern
coast, Hannay said he would hold talks with Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash as well
as other officials to prepare the ground for the talks.
</P>
<P>
However, the envoy did not go into details about the
discussions,
citing an appeal by the U.N. for a news blackout on public
statements concerning the talks.
</P>
<P>
These matters "are familiar", he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, Hannay is the first of several
foreign envoys to visit Cyprus ahead of the third round of talks,
which were scheduled to start on July 5 in Geneva to pave the way
for a settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Next week U.N. Secretary-General's Special Advisor for Cyprus
Alvaro de Soto will come here on a similar mission and U.S.
Presidential Emissary Alfred Moses is expected to come a few days
later.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The two communities have held two rounds of proximity-talks
under the U.N. auspices in an effort to find a solution to the
Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
