<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N., OAU to Probe into Alleged Extrajudicial Executions in Togo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Wednesday set up a commission
to investigate the deaths of hundreds of people allegedly murdered
by security forces in Togo.
</P>
<P>
A three-man commission of inquiry will look into "allegations
that hundreds of people were victims of extrajudicial executions
in Togo in 1998," the two organizations said in a statement issued
here.
</P>
<P>
The commission, chaired by Mahamat Hassan Abakar of Chad, "is
being established at the initiative of the government of Togo,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The government of Togo called a report a "fabric of lies"
which claimed hundreds of people were murdered after elections in
June 1998, but urged the U.N. and the OAU to set up the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The commission will be based at the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights in Geneva and will "undertake its
work in the field," the statement said. "Appropriate consultations
will take place, including with the Togolese authorities and
others in a position to assist the commission."  
</P>
</TEXT>
