<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Holbrook Warns Impacts of Male Control of High Tech on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7 (Xinhua -- U.S. Ambassador to the United
Nations, Richard Holbrook, warned on Wednesday that male control
of the high tech would probably result in women's suffering as
earlier generations did when innovative farming methods were
introduced.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a forum at a global United Nations Meeting aimed at
achieving equality between men and women, Holbrook said" The new
technologies are a chance for women to close the gender gap of the
Third World, but they are also a danger."
</P>
<P>
"Don't let the men control the process, because for explicit or
implicit, conscious or subconscious reasons," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said the agricultural revolution of 30 years ago,
which introduced such technologies as irrigation and fertilizers
to the developing world, was expected to benefit women, but had
the opposite effects.
</P>
<P>
"If the international community ...had a training program for
the new technologies, the men took all the positions in the
classes. It was stunning and nobody saw it coming,' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
