<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Successfully Tests Anti-Rocket Laser Gun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The test of the Tactical High Energy Laser (THEL) was conducted
at the White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico State of the United
States at 5:48 p.m. local time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was the first in a series before the high-energy laser is
to be handed over to Israel to protect its northern borders
against short-range rocket threats. The laser gun was described as
"the world's first high-energy laser weapon system designed for
operational use."
</P>
<P>
"We've just turned science fiction into reality," Lieutenant
General John Costello of the U.S. Army Space and Missile Defense
Command commented on the test.
</P>
<P>
"This compelling demonstration of THEL's defensive capabilities
proves that directed energy weapon systems have the potential to
play a significant role in defending U.S. national security
interests worldwide," Costello said.
</P>
<P>
The laser's ability to shoot down multiple rockets will be
tested this summer, according to military sources.
</P>
<P>
If those tests succeed, the United States expects to ship the
laser to Israel this fall.
</P>
<P>
U.S. defense officials have said Israel would need more laser
weapons to protect its whole northern border from rocket attacks
by Hizbollah guerrillas, who took over areas vacated by Israeli
forces in southern Lebanon in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
