<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Government Sets Targets to Cut Work-Related Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The British government and the
Health and Safety Commission (HSC) Wednesday announced targets for
the nation to reduce work-related deaths, ill-health and injury in
the country.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest health and safety shake-up for 25 years.
Over 1 million workers are injured every year in Britain.
Accidents and ill-health among the work force cost the British
economy up to 8 billion pounds (12.8 billion U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
The British government and the HSC decided there was now a need
to take a fresh look at health and safety policy in general to
give it fresh impetus and gain further improvements.
</P>
<P>
Among the specific targets were: to reduce the number of
working days lost from work-related injury and ill-health by 30
percent by the year 2010; reduce the incidence of people suffering
from work-related ill-health by 20 percent by the year 2010; and
reduce the rate of fatal and major injury accidents by 10 percent
by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The government and the HSC also introduced a 10-point strategy
which will provide incentives and practical support to employers,
together with a range of measures to tackle employers who do not
meet their health and safety responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The strategy highlights that the health and safety system must
promote a better working environment as well as prevent harm.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott said: "Health and safety is
a priority issue for those at the top of all organizations and
they must be prepared to face the consequences of ignoring the law;
in future that could well mean prison." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
