<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asylum Seekers in Britain Face Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Immigration Service
Wednesday announced plans to speed up the deportation of asylum
seekers after their applications are rejected.
</P>
<P>
The move was aimed at removing nearly 60,000 people a year by
2004, compared to 12,000 this year, the BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
A key part of the new radical plan for change would see more
detention centers built.
</P>
<P>
There are currently 900 detention spaces in the UK for asylum
seekers but officials are proposing that 4,000 be created.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 8,000 asylum seekers who lost their claims were
removed from Britain last year.
</P>
<P>
Discrepancies remain between the numbers refused asylum and
those who were actually forced to leave the UK.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Immigration Service's enforcement directorate
confirmed that they were working to new, much tougher targets.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that 12,000 people would be removed from Britain
this year, rising to 30,000 between 2001 and 2002, and to 37,000
the following year. That total would be expected to rise to 57,000
by 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
