<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Status Return to ELN Opens Colombian Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian government decision to
return the National Liberation Army (ELN) guerrilla its political
status opens new opportunities to negotiate the zone of distention
both sides agreed to create in the north of the country, Attorney
General Jaime Bernal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the urgent matters to be addressed now is, according to
Bernal, to have the communities of the region to accept the
establishment of the "zone of encounter" that will serve as the
venue for this new peace process, the second after the one opened
by the government with the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia
(FARC).
</P>
<P>
President Andres Pastrana's government declared open "the
process of dialogue" with the ELN in a resolution issued Tuesday,
in which it returned to the rebel group its political status.
</P>
<P>
This status had been granted to the ELN on October 9, 1998, but
was withdrawn on June 18, 1999, after that guerrilla force
kidnapped more than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
The government and the ELN, the second most important insurgent
group in the country after the FARC, agreed, according to a
preliminary accord published in April of this year, that the
neutral area would include the Cantagallo, San Pablo, and Yondo
localities, the first two ones in the Bolivar department and the
third in Antioquia.
</P>
<P>
But residents of the region rejected that possibility by
erecting roadblocks on the roads that connect Colombia's inland
regions with the northern coast, a protest that was lifted in a
negotiated way on June 1, after three weeks of a conflict in which
the extreme right took part, according to several sources.
</P>
<P>
The government promised then to the leaders of the residents of
the region to leave in suspension the "zone of encounter" with the
ELN and to discuss with the communities its eventual establishment
in that place of the north of Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Govt Targets Sustainable Reduction of Poverty (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government's main
medium and long term objective "is the sustainable reduction of
poverty through the establishment of an environment that generates
economic growth", a newly released government keynote document
said.
</P>
<P>
The document will be submitted to a meeting of the World Bank's
 Consultative Group on Mozambique to be held in Paris on Thursday
and Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Consultative Group is a forum at which the government
presents donors and funding agencies with the economy's financial
requirements for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics available show that about 70 percent of the
Mozambican population has been sunk in poverty since 1997 and the
government hopes to cut this to 50 percent by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 there were 11.3 million Mozambicans living in absolute
poverty. Even if the government succeeds in cutting the incidence
of poverty to 50 percent, there will still be 10.8 million poor
Mozambicans in 2010 because of the exponential population growth
(currently running at 2.3 percent a year).
</P>
<P>
The government also promises to fix intermediary objectives to
ensure that the 2010 target is reached, to draw up clear and
specific anti-poverty actions at regional, sector and national
levels, and to design a monitoring system to follow the success
(or otherwise) of the anti-poverty measures.
</P>
<P>
The government is optimistic that over the coming decade, the
country's economic growth can be maintained at 9 to 10 percent per
annum.
</P>
<P>
However, it admits that for this year growth will be 2 or 3
percentage points lower, because of the catastrophic floods in
southern and central Mozambique in February.
</P>
<P>
The government also hopes that over the next decade inflation
can be kept to between 5 and 7 percent a year. However, for this
year the price rises triggered by the floods had resulted in an
inflation of 10 percent in the first four months.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, public expenditure will rise from
about 800 million U.S. dollars in 1999 to about 1.9 billion
dollars in 2010, while tax revenue and other domestic sources of
income are expected to generate about 1.3 billion dollars in 2010,
leaving some 600 million dollars to come from foreign donors and
creditors.
</P>
<P>
In percentage terms, the government expects the dependence of
the state budget on foreign aid to fall from 60 percent in 1998 to
slightly more than 30 percent in 2010.
</P>
<P>
But in absolute terms, the need for foreign aid will continue
to rise -- from 514 million dollars in 2001 to 568 million in
2005, and 586 million in 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Govt Targets Sustainable Reduction of Poverty (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mozambique will this year need 504 million U.S. dollars,
against the 425.9 million dollars pledged by donors in Rome early
this May for post- flood reconstruction, to ensure the smooth
running of the national economy, the document said.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's per capita gross domestic product (GDP) had risen
from 145 U.S. dollars in 1995 to more than 240 dollars in 1999,
the document said, noting that "this means that Mozambique is no
longer the poorest country in the world", the label regularly
stuck on the country in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The document estimated that if the government's plans come to
fruition, the per capita GDP of the country should reach between
375 and 400 U.S. dollars by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The document called once more upon creditors to scrap
Mozambique's foreign debt in its entirety, saying "the effects of
the war on the human, social and infrastructural fabric of the
country, plus the enormous devastation caused by the recent
natural disasters impose the need for a total write-off of the
foreign debt."
</P>
<P>
Such a total debt cancellation would allow resources currently
spent on debt servicing "to be channelled towards the main goal of
creating a climate that generates economic growth, and towards
poverty reduction", the document said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government welcomes the cancellation of 3.4
billion U.S. dollars of debt (in nominal terms) last year under
the HIPC (Heavily Indebted Poor Countries) initiative, and the
steps under way for Mozambique to qualify for further relief under
"enhanced HIPC".
</P>
<P>
The government's projections for future budgets rely heavily on
indirect taxation, particularly on the Value Added Tax (VAT) that
was introduced last year.
</P>
<P>
VAT should account for an enormous 36 percent of total state
revenue in 2010, compared with 23 percent in 1999, the document
said. Customs revenue will play a much less pivotal role in
government income than in the past because of the gradual
reduction of tariffs with neighboring states, the document said,
adding that tariffs will decline to zero with all SADC (Southern
African Development Community) states except South Africa in eight
years.
</P>
<P>
However, the document makes no mention at all of property
taxes. Currently, the top band of income tax is an extraordinarily
low 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Passes Referendum Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Parliament has passed the
Referendum (Political Systems) Bill 2000 which was challenged by
chief of the Democratic Party Paul Ssemogerere, Radio Uganda
reported Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which should have come into effect on July 2, 1999,
was passed without any amendment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The bill aims to make provision for the holding of the
referendum required under the Ugandan Constitution, the report
said, adding that it will determine the political system the
people of Uganda are to adopt.
</P>
<P>
It will fulfil the aspirations of the people of Uganda by
guaranteeing them a political system of their own choice, the
report quoted members of parliament as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to James Wapakabulo, national political commissar and
member of Parliament, the bill is well intentioned and is
guaranteed by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Ssemogerere had filed a petition challenging the referendum law
on the grounds that it was passed without a quorum, but his
petition was dismissed by the Constitutional Court, which said
that the courts have no power to inquire into the internal
procedures of the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
