<HEADLINE> Door Still Open for Resuming Syrian-Israeli Talks: Syrian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Syria left the door open for the
resumption of the Syria-Israeli peace negotiations, said Syrian
Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Syria has no objection to the U.S. viewpoint that there are
chances to resume the Syrian-Israeli talks, and is ready to seek
revival of the talks on the return of the Golan Heights, Shareh
told reporters after meeting here with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
He said that Syria agreed to resume contacts and intensify
exchange of views with the U.S. as Washington believes there is
still a chance to reach a just and comprehensive peace in the
Middle East before U.S. President Bill Clinton leaves office in
2001.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Cairo earlier in the day for a day-long
visit after two-day visits to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule
areas to discuss the Syrian-Israeli peace talks with Shareh, who
was in the Egyptian capital for Arab meetings.
</P>
<P>
Albright did not speak to reporters after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Before her meeting with Shareh, Albright held talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to brief him on the latest
developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks. The two sides
have agreed to hold negotiations near Washington early next week.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. State Department official said that Shareh told
Albright that Syria "would like to find a way" to reopen
negotiations with Israel. But "it is going to take some time before
we get a resumption of the talks," the official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Shareh, meanwhile, stressed that Syria would not sacrifice Arab
rights, defined as recovering all the territories occupied by
Israel in the 1967 Mideast war, including Syria's Golan Heights,
and restoring the legitimate rights of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks broke down last January due to
disputes over Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights and the
control of water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
