<HEADLINE> Iraqi Children Wounded in Left-over Bomb Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi boys have been injured
when a bomb believed to be left over from the 1991 Gulf War
exploded, a local report said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The incident happened in the Al-Dair town, some 40 kilometers
north of the Al-Basra city in the southern Basra Province, the
report said. No exact time was given.
</P>
<P>
The two wounded boys, identified as 8-year-old Satar Hamdan Aziz
and 12-year-old Jabar Hamdan Aziz, were sent to hospital
immediately for emergency treatment.
</P>
<P>
The previous such incident occurred on April 9 when a bomb went
off, wounding two women, named as Saada Abbas Shalan and Jawahir
Faris Shalan, 60 kilometers west of the capital Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Gulf War and the ensuing bombings by the
U.S. and British planes over the two no-fly zones in southern and
northern Iraq, have left many unexploded bombs, thus posing threat
to people's life.
</P>
<P>
To avoid civilian casualties, Iraqi civil defense has been
engaged in the arduous work of defusing unexploded cluster bombs.
Over 56,000 bombs and a cruise missile left over from the 1991 Gulf
War and the regular U.S.-British bombardments have been defused.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi civil defense has warned that citizens must not approach
or touch unknown objects, let alone take unexploded bombs to their
houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
