<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Barak in Three-Option Political Dilemma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset (Parliament)
Wednesday morning gave preliminary approval to a motion calling for
early elections, a move that may threaten the survival of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's fragile coalition government and the whole
Middle East peace process in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Although Wednesday's voting is only for the preliminary reading
of the bill, which still waits for going through the Knesset Law
Committee and three more readings, its passage with a 61-48 margin
was already regarded as a warning to Barak's government.
</P>
<P>
Barak is now facing a three-option political dilemma in the most
serious coalition crisis since he took office last July.
</P>
<P>
But all the options, whatever Barak chooses, will no doubt cast
shadow over Israel's peace talks with the Palestinians and other
Arab countries, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
Since three ruling partners in Barak's coalition -- Shas,
Yisrael Ba'aliya, National Religious Party (NRP) -- voted along
opposition parties during Wednesday morning's Knesset showdown, the
first option for Barak is to eat his words and resume talks with
the powerful ultra-Orthodox Shas party over its demands for more
government funding for its nearly bankrupt Orthodox educational
network.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Shas will re-endorse the government once it
gets the cash and Yisrael Ba'aliya will also not quit the coalition
once its demands are met.
</P>
<P>
The three right-wing parties carried out their rebellion even
though officials in Barak's office pledged to kick them out of the
government if they voted against the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
It should be noted that should Barak fulfil his threats finally,
his administration will surely be dwarfed from a 68-52 majority to
a 42-member minority in the 120-seat Knesset, with the loss of the
17 seats of Shas, the five seats of the NRP, and the four seats of
Yisrael Ba'aliya.
</P>
<P>
Barak's concession will keep his government's majority intact,
but Barak will suffer a serious blow in the eyes of the public. The
patched-up coalition is only waiting for another major crisis once
the insatiable parties feel hungry again.
</P>
<P>
Such an option will also tie Barak's hands under the negotiation
table with the Palestinians and the Syrians, as those hawkish
parties are inclined to oppose making more concessions to the
Palestinians and Syria regarding the Israeli withdrawal
respectively from the West Bank and Gaza Strip and from the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians are currently in talks to reach a
final-status framework agreement and a final peace accord before
the September 13 deadline. They will begin a new round of talks in
Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
The second option for Barak is to fire the ministers and deputy
ministers of the three rebelling parties and recruit new partners
from Shinui, Democratic List, and Am Ehad, which will build up a
minority government with 52 seats in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Depending upon 10 votes from Israeli Arabs' parties, the
government may push forward peace proposals with the Palestinians
through the Knesset with a thin majority.
</P>
<P>
In such a difficult-to-manage government, Barak will refrain
from taking risks to launch controversial and dauntless peace
initiatives with the Palestinians, such as peace plans about the
fate of Jerusalem, the dismantling of Jewish settlements in the
West Bank, and the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, having run into a moment of truth, the Israeli-
Palestinian peace track is in dire need of such initiatives to
resolve thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace track is also waiting for daring
proposals to reopen.
</P>
<P>
The final option for the Israeli prime minister is to resort to
Israeli people and embrace an early election.
</P>
<P>
"I won't hesitate, if necessary, to go straight to the Israeli
people, and the people will know how to judge the behavior of
those, who will interrupt this mission (the peace process)," Barak
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Historically, an identical early-election legislation passed a
preliminary reading in July 1998 against then Benjamin Netanyahu's
government, which was seemingly harmless at first but toppled the
then regime later.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, a new election will not happen in six to 10 months, as
the bill has to go through the Knesset legislative procedure,
leaving plenty of time for political maneuvering, and there were
indications that some ruling coalition legislators who backed the
bill simply wanted to send a warning to Barak.
</P>
<P>
However, the uncertainty during the transition time between now
and the final reading of the early-election bill will drain Barak's
attention from the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Barak may have to play tough to the Palestinians
and the Syrians during the campaign for a new election to attract
voters as many as possible. Such a tough stand may result in
deadlocks in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian and Syrian leaders, Barak's negotiating rivals,
will also adopt a wait-and-see attitude toward the peace talks as
long as they can not ascertain the survival of the Barak
administration.
</P>
<P>
They don't want to negotiate with a loser in the internal
crisis, and history has proved that the delay itself is a major
threat to the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
