<HEADLINE> Most French People Approve Shortening Presidential Term: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-three percent of French voters
approve the shortening of presidential term from seven to five
years, said a poll published on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted on June 6 on telephone with 1,012 people by
the IPSOS polling institute and Le Point weekly, showed that a
majority of people from all political orientations of France will
vote for the constitutional reform in a referendum expected to be
held at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac proposed on Monday that France
hold a referendum on shortening the seven-year presidential term,
which he said is too long and does not meet the requests of a
democratic system today.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year presidential term came down from the Third
Republic of France established in 1871 and was adopted by
President Charles de Gaulle in his 1962 Constitution of the Fifth
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Socialist government adopted on Wednesday a
draft law on reforming the presidential term which will be
presented to the National Assembly on June 14 and the Senate June
30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
