<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Important Findings in U.N. Report" Progress of the World's Women 2000" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7(Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Fund for Women (UNIFEM) launched here Wednesday a
biennial report titled "Progress of the World's Women 2000".
</P>
<P>
The report assesses how globalization impacts women's lives
using three indicators: gender equality in secondary education
enrollment, women's share of seats in parliament, and women's
share of paid employment.
</P>
<P>
Following are the important findings of the report:
</P>
<P>
WOMEN"S SHARE OF SEATS IN PARLIAMENT
</P>
<P>
Eastern Europe has suffered the most dramatic decreases of
women's seats in parliament, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Of the 24 nations in Western Europe and other developed
countries, the United States ranks 19 in the number of seats held
by women in congress. The United States has reached 12 percent,
followed by Italy (10 percent), Malta(9.2 percent), France(9.1
percent), Japan(8.3 percent) and Greece(6.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
Women's share of seats in parliament increased in 17 developed
and developing countries from 1987 to 2000, most notably because
of governmental positive action and quotas.
</P>
<P>
Eight countries have achieved the goal of at least a 30
percent share of seats held by women in parliament. They are:
Denmark, Finland, Germany, Iceland, Netherlands, Norway, South
Africa and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
GIRLS ENROLMENT IN SECONDARY EDUCATION DETERIORATES IN SUB-
SAHARAN AFRICA
</P>
<P>
The level of girl's enrollment in secondary education has
seriously deteriorated in much of sub-Saharan Africa, and the
report draws linkage between increased indebtedness and declines
in enrollment. Of the 15 countries with decreases in girls'
enrollment, 12 also showed an increase in national debt.
</P>
<P>
While 11 percent of countries have achieved gender equality in
secondary education enrollment, there have been decreases in: 11
out of 33 countries in sub-Saharan Africa; 7 out 11 countries in
Central and Western Asia; 6 out of 26 countries in Latin America
and the Caribbean and 6 out 9 countries in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
WOMEN'S SHARE OF PAID EMPLOYMENT
</P>
<P>
Much of women's work is invisible to economic decision makers,
particularly unpaid"caring" work and the informal sector labor of
street vendors and home-based workers.
</P>
<P>
In terms of economic transition, when State-run businesses
privatize and a market economy is ushered in, women and girls
often pay the price, especially when services such as day care and
health care are cut back.
</P>
<P>
Women typically provide around 70 percent of the time spent on
unpaid care work within the family while men provide around 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
There are only a few countries in the world where women's share
of paid employment in industry and services in around 50 percent,
and handful in which it is somewhat higher.
</P>
<P>
The report found that from the mid-1980s to the late 1990s,
women's share of paid employment had increased in most regions,
with the exception of parts of Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1990s, the share ranged from a high of 54 percent
in Ukraine and Latvia to 5 percent in Chad.
</P>
<P>
Of the 24 Western Europe and other developed countries, the
United States ranked sixth with 48 percent. The lowest shares were
in Luxembourg with 36 percent and Malta with 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with Western Europe and other developed nations, the
United States has the highest share of women in administrative and
managerial positions. From the mid-1980s to the late 1990s, the
United States's share of women in administrative and managerial
positions increased from 38 percent to 47 percent, compared with
the United Kingdom with 22 to 23 percent, Canada with 35 to 40
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Denies Amnesty International Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization on Wednesday denied an accusation by Amnesty
International that the western military alliance deliberately
targeted civilians during last year's 78-day air strikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The London-based international human rights watchdog released a
60-page report which has alleged that NATO's bombing of the Serb
Radio and Television station, in which 16 people were killed,
constituted a war crime.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General George Robertson said in a written
statement that the Amnesty International accusation was "baseless
and ill-founded".
</P>
<P>
The Briton quoted Carla del Ponte, chief prosecutor of the
United Nations International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia, as saying that there was no deliberate targeting of
civilians or of unlawful military targets by NATO during the
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
Del Ponte made the remark at last week's U.N. Security Council
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said that the western military alliance"
scrupulously adhered to international law, including the law of
war, throughout the conflict and made every effort to minimize
civilian casualties".
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that mistakes were made or weapons
malfunctioned leading to civilian deaths or injuries.
</P>
<P>
On April 11 last year, NATO war planes bombed a civilian train
travelling on a bridge in southern Serbia, killing more than 10
people and injuring dozens.
</P>
<P>
On April 14 last year, NATO war planes bombed a civilian convoy
of Kosovar Albanians and caused more than 70 deaths in
southwestern Kosovo. It took NATO days to acknowledge the fact
that civilians were bombed and killed in that incident.
</P>
<P>
On April 20 last year, NATO war planes targeted the
headquarters of the Serb Radio and Television station killing 16
people working on night shift.
</P>
<P>
NATO also bombed civilian coaches travelling inside Kosovo
killing Kosovar Albanians on these occasions.
</P>
<P>
NATO also bombed Yugoslav power grids and running-water supply
systems, causing great difficulties to the civilians of the Balkan
country.
</P>
<P>
NATO bombed factories that manufactured motor vehicles,noodles,
electrical fans, vacuum cleaners and other household utilities as
well.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav authorities gave the casualty of civilians during
the NATO air strikes at more than 1,000 deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Extends Its Peacekeepers' Presence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Federation Council, upper
house of parliament, Wednesday unanimously voted for prolonging
the presence of the Russian peacekeeping troops in the Yugoslavia
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The prolongation was proposed by Russian President Vladimir
Putin on Wednesday, Federation Council speaker Yegor Stroyev told
the upper house before the voting.
</P>
<P>
Exactly a year ago, under the understandings reached by Group-8
foreign ministers peacekeeping contingents were sent to the
breakaway province from NATO states and neutral countries, and
from Russia -- at Yugoslavia's special request.
</P>
<P>
On June 25, 1999, the Federation Council at an extraordinary
closed-door session gave its consent to the participation of
Russian troops in the international peacekeeping operation in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The total size of the Russian force in Kosovo is 3,616 persons,
currently divided into five battalions, control bodies, logistical
units and an airdrome service unit.
</P>
<P>
Russian peacekeepers do not have their own control sector in
Kosovo, therefore they have to operate in the British, American,
German and French sectors.
</P>
<P>
Now the number of Russian peacekeepers abroad tops to over 10,
000,ranking second after the United States. The Russian units are
mainly deployed in Bosnia, Kosovo, Moldova, Tajikistan, the North
Caucasus' South Ossetia and Abkhazia regions, as well as in some
African conflicting states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Calls for Urgent Security Council Meeting on DRC Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda has called on the U.N.
Security Council to convene an urgent meeting to discuss the
renewed fighting between its troops and Ugandan forces in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the president of the 15-nation Council,
published here Wednesday, Joseph Mutaboba, the Rwandan permanent
representative to the United Nations, said, "Uganda should be
seriously condemned" for starting the fighting in the city of
Kisangani, which broke out Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan ambassador, in his letter, said that Rwanda wished
to see U.N. observers on the ground "taking the right positions or
actions, instead of trying to please the two sides or apportion
blame."
</P>
<P>
He said that Rwanda remains committed to the Lusaka peace
accord, which, he said, is the only feasible framework for the
settlement of the crisis in the DRC and the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no reaction yet from the Ugandan side.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council met Tuesday and condemned the fighting.
In a statement read to the press after the meeting, the Council
president, Jean David-Levitte of France, said, "armed engagements
between the two foreign armies of Rwanda and Uganda on the
territory of the DRC" were incompatible with the Lusaka cease-fire
agreement, signed by six African countries in the Zambian capital
of Lusaka on July 10.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 civilians have been killed in fighting which
raged for a third day Wednesday between Rwandan and Ugandan
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials and aid workers put the death toll at more than
50 civilians, including at least 19 children, since the beginning
of the fighting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda used to be strong allies but now back
different rebel factions fighting in the DRC and have clashed
several times for control of Kisangani, a center of the vast
nation's diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting came as both sides were in the process of
withdrawing from Kisangani under the agreement reached last month
in which each was to pull troops and heavy weapons back 100
kilometers from the city center and leave 216 soldiers each in
town to guard strategic installations.
</P>
<P>
It began on Monday morning when Ugandan troops shelled Rwandan
positions in response to an attack on a Ugandan army vehicle by
unidentified assailants, reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
