<HEADLINE> Greek FM Stresses Importance of Fully Implementation of Stability Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou Wednesday stressed the importance of the Balkan
countries to assume the responsibility for the successfully
implementation of the Stability Pact in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after the end of the Balkan
foreign ministers informal meeting in the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki, Papandreou said that the countries in the region
were willing to play an even bigger role in the materialization of
the Stability Pact.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that there were bureaucracy problems that must
be faced immediately.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou described Serbia as the "black hole" of the Balkans
because without it the reconstruction could not proceed.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed both his and his Balkan counterparts'
full support towards the Montenegro government, citing the need
for dialogue between Montenegro and the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was held within the framework of the
Stability Pact, was attended by the foreign ministers of Greece,
Croatia, Macedonia and Montenegro, as well as the foreign
undersecretaries or bureau chiefs from Bosnia-Herzegovina, Albania,
Slovenia, Italy, Turkey, Hungary, Bulgaria and Romania. The
European Union's high representative for common foreign policy and
security, Javier Solana, and Stability Pact special coordinator
Bodo Hombach also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou reiterated Greece's opposition to any changes in
the Balkan region's borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
