<HEADLINE> NATO Condemns Border Trouble-Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- NATO on Wednesday condemned
trouble-makers along the border between the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
But the western military alliance stopped short of identifying
the ethnic nationality of the trouble-makers, only saying that it
condemned the recent attacks against the border guards of the
former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
It added that the alliance is committed to cooperating with the
authorities of Macedonia to strengthen security at the border.
</P>
<P>
NATO acknowledged receiving a letter from Macedonian President
Boris Trajkovski requesting further consultations with NATO-led
peacekeeping troops in Kosovo and possible NATO assistance on
border security matters.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia on Wednesday increased its military presence along
the border with Kosovo and the country is giving out an order on
June 15 for raised military readiness.
</P>
<P>
Macedonian government officials said that the Balkan nation has
to act after two Macedonian border guards were shot from inside
Kosovo, now a de facto protectorate of NATO and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
It was the second incident in two months. In early April, a
group of Kosovar Albanians kidnapped four Macedonian border guards
who were later released.
</P>
<P>
NATO has promised to consider the issues in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers are meeting in their scheduled council
on Thursday and Friday this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
