<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Council urges Iraq to Cooperate With UNMOVIC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7(Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Wednesday called on Iraq to cooperate with the United
Nations Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission(UNMOVIC)
in implementing U.N. resolution 1284.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council considered this
morning the first trimestrial report of UNMOVIC and heard a
briefing by its Executive Chairman, Hans Blix.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated its support for the Executive
Chairman and his action in implementing Security Council
resolution 1284 adopted late last year. The resolution established
UNMOVIC and defined its mandate.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reaffirmed that the cooperation of the
Government of Iraq is essential to implementing resolutions 1284
and before the Council can decide to suspend and, afterwards, lift
the sanctions against the country which has been in place since
1990.
</P>
<P>
The new arms regime for Iraq, UNMOVIC, was created to replace
the United Nations Special Commission( UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM withdrew from Iraq days before the U.S-led military
strikes against Iraq in December 1998 and Iraq has barred it from
returning since then.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. resolution 1284, UNMOVIC will be in charge of
Iraq's chemical, biological and ballistic-missle programs.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has refused to cooperate with UNMOVIC, saying lifting the
sanctions is the precondition for the U.N. arms inspectors to
return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique: Gas Pipeline to Be Environment Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- An 800-km-long pipeline project to
be built between the gas fields in the southern Mozambican
province of Inhambane, and South Africa, will be environment
friendly.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will cost 900 million U.S. dollars, is to
transport natural gas from the Temane and Pande fields, in
Inhambane, to South Africa, Wednesday's "Noticias" newspaper
reported,
</P>
<P>
The pipes will be buried one meter deep, and no building is to
be erected within a space of three meters on either side od the
pipeline, the newspaper quoted Marja Prinsloo, an environment
expert, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The pipe will be covered with a kind of material which will
prevent leaks that damage the environment", said Prinsloo, adding
that the quality of this material is guaranteed for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Prinsloo explained that the technology to be used to install
and operate the pipeline has been used successfully in several
other countries, including South Africa. She expected it to have
the same success in Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
