<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Corruption in S. Africa Calls for New Moral Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A new moral order is the only
means of reversing corruption in South Africa, said Free State
Premier Winkie Direko on Wednesday at a public service
anti-corruption workshop held in the judicial capital of
Bloemfontein.
</P>
<P>
"We pledge action against corruption and those engaging in
corrupt practices -- and yet we still see the scourge of
corruption growing and growing like a giant snowball and
threatening to engulf us," she said.
</P>
<P>
She warned that "unless we succeed in bringing about a new
moral order in this country, no code of conduct or policy will
save us and we might as well give in to corruption."
</P>
<P>
Public servants should learn to put their own desires on hold
in the interests of the country and of a sound government, she
said, urging teachers to set a careful example to their pupils,
and parents to show their children that they abide by the law, pay
their dues and respect the constitution.
</P>
<P>
One of the first steps needed is to instil in children a
respect for the property of others, Direko said.
</P>
<P>
"Part of our struggle was to break whatever we came across --
anything from school windows to street lamps. Now has come the
time that we must teach our children to respect property," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Direko also urged public servants to blow the whistle on
corrupt colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Free State director-general Khotso de Wee told the
workshop that 345 cases of corruption have been reported in the
provincial education department since January of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 107 involved check fraud, 12 were related to the
alleged misuse of government vehicles, and seven involved alleged
fraudulent subsistence and travel allowance claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
