<HEADLINE> Fight Against Cross Border Crime in Southern Africa Satisfactory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Southern Africa
Regional Police Chiefs Cooperation Organization and Commissioner
Edgar Hillary of Swaziland Wednesday commended the achievements
the organization has made in combating cross border crime in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied with the results we have so far achieved in
combating cross border crime like drug trafficking and other crime
syndicates," he said, noting that "this shows that we are not
paying lip-service to crime, but we are being practical."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hillary pointed out that the organization is facing
problems with repatriating exhibits as the laws differ from
country to country.
</P>
<P>
"The other challenge we are facing is that of increasing
conflicts in the region like the war in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo," he said, adding that "this results in firearms
crossing borders and being used to commit crime."
</P>
<P>
According to Hillary, the Interpol sub-regional bureau to be
set up next year in Harare would enhance the organization's
activities.
</P>
<P>
Hillary started his visit to the region on May 28 and has been
to Mozambique, Malawi and Tanzania. From Zimbabwe he will visit
Zambia before returning to Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
The southern African regional organization was formed in 1995
with the view to cooperate in combating cross border crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
