<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda Agree on Ceasefire in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan and Rwandan troops
managed to achieve a ceasefire on Wednesday in Kisangani, a
northeastern city of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC),
after skirmishes between the two armies broke out on Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) and the Rwanda
Patriotic Army (RPA) agreed to cease fire in Kisangani at 00:45
a.m. local time Wednesday," Ugandan Army Spokesman Phinehas
katirima told Xinhua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Katirima, both sides had agreed to pull out their
troops 700 meters off the Tchopo Bridge.
</P>
<P>
He said Uganda and Rwanda will continue to implement the
withdrawal plan and the demilitarization of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan armies went into clashes after a UPDF's
vehicle was attacked and destroyed in Kisangani Monday morning.
The UPDF had by Tuesday night repulsed RPA forces attacking UPDF
positions in Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
According to the withdrawal plan, Kisangani is divided into
different zones and the demilitarization will be carried out in
different phases.
</P>
<P>
The first phase, which is supposed to take five days, involves
the demilitarization of zone one which includes Bangoka Airport,
La Forestiere and Lubutu junction areas.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, which should have started on Monday, aims to
realize the pull-out from the town, Simi Simi Airport and
Kapalata.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have their troops stationed in Kisangani
where they have supported rival rebel factions fighting against
DRC President Laurent Kabila. The skirmishes on Monday and Tuesday
between the two armies are the latest following the clashes early
last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
