<HEADLINE> Anti-Desertification Trees Dried Up in Southwest Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 15,000 trees planted in the
past eight months in an area of about 14 hectares as a treatment
for the desertification in the Angolan southwest Namibe Province
have recently been found dried up.
</P>
<P>
According to Romao Kambuandi, who is responsible for the anti-
desertification project, the disaster was mainly due to lack of
irrigation as the irrigation workers stopped their work following
the cut-off of food provision for them.
</P>
<P>
Under the "work for food" program sponsored by the World Food
Program, the organization should offer food to the workers and
clerks employed by local public services.
</P>
<P>
The anti-desertification project, located in Tombua City, began
in 1985 with the help of the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organization which invested 1 million U.S. dollars in the project.
</P>
<P>
The cultured forest covers an 8,000-meter-long and
300-meter-wide area along the edge of the desert in the southwest
region of Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
