<HEADLINE> Cambodia, Thailand End Discussion on Border Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia and Thailand Wednesday
ended three days of discussion on ways to resolve a protracted
border dispute and expressed their hopes to start demarcation by
next year, the head of the Thai delegation told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Sukhumbhand Paribatra, the Thai deputy foreign minister who
leads the Thai delegation, said after the meeting that the
discussion, which was held in a constructive and friendly
atmosphere, was fruitful and produced tangible results.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia claims Thailand has encroached on some parts of its
803-km-long common border in northern and western Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"No one quite knows where the exact boundary is. If every one
of us knows where exactly the boundary is, then we don't have a
job," Sukhumbhand told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the Cambodian-Thai Joint Commission on
Demarcation for Land Boundary was held in the middle of last year
in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, a memorandum of understanding (MoU) on the
survey and demarcation of the land boundary, and agreed minutes on
the Terms of Reference and a master plan for the joint survey and
demarcation of the common land boundary -- were signed.
</P>
<P>
It remains unclear whether Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai,
who is due to visit Cambodia on June 14-16, will continue to
discuss the border issue with Cambodian officials, but it is
expected that the MOU will be processed during his visit.
</P>
<P>
The MoU is aimed at surveying and demarcating the land boundary
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
