<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Rise on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) surged up 33.15 points
to close at 2,034.87 points maintaining the upturn for the fifth
consecutive session this month.
</P>
<P>
The total volume rose to 536.37 million shares worth 912.17
million Singapore dollars (529.35 million U.S. dollars). Advancing
issues led decliners by 180 to 153 with 208 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Achieva topped the actives chart registering a turnover of 35.
71 million shares. Medi-Rad was the second most heavily traded
stock with 26.35 million units traded. It was followed by Trek
which had 24.40 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH was the biggest gainer of the day surging up 110 cents to a
close at 27.50 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 finished the day 100
cents higher at 27.40 Singapore dollars. DBS and OCBC picked up 60
cents to end at 22.20 and 11.50 Singapore dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Venture and Creative 50 headed the descent of the day giving up
80 cents each to close at 46.80 and 19.10 Singapore dollars
separately. GreatEast shed 30 cents to finish at 5.70 Singapore
dollars. ST Assemb retreated 25 cents to end at 6.25 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that there was follow-through buying from the day
before, with some blue chips attracting interest from bargain-
hunter.
</P>
<P>
They noted bargain hunting, especially big cap stocks such as
SPH and DBS, helped push the STI higher.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts were unsure if the rally could sustain.
</P>
