<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNIFEM Launches Biennial Report"Progress of the World's Women 2000"  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7 (Xinhua -- The United Nations
Development Fund for Women (UNIFEM) on Wednesday launched here a
biennial report "Progress of the World's Women 2000".
</P>
<P>
The report assesses how globalization impacts women's lives
using three indicators: gender quality in secondary education
enrollment, women's share of seats in parliament, and women's
share of paid employment.
</P>
<P>
The report shows during the last decade, only eight nations
have successfully met goals agreed upon by governments at a series
of United Nations Conferences in the 1990s, to achieve both gender
equality in secondary education enrollment and at least a 30
percent share of seats held by women in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The report draws attention to the fact that there are no
globally agreed time-bound targets relating to women's economic
equality and recommends the adoption of such specific targets.
</P>
<P>
Its data relating to women's economic status reveals that
women's share of paid employment has increased in most regions,
with the exception of parts of Eastern Europe, and that women's
share of administrative and managerial employment has increased in
51 of the 59 countries for which data was available.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Noeleen Heyzer, Executive Director of
the UNIFEM and chief sponsor of the new biennial report, said "We
need to learn from countries where women have achieved 30 percent
of seats in parliament and participate in key decision-making,
particularly in the realm of government expenditures and the
formulation of economic policy."
</P>
<P>
"This report forcefully reminds governments and corporations
that more people will benefit from globalization if women are
active in setting agendas and reshaping global economic rules,
Heyzer said,
</P>
<P>
 "UNIFEM is urgently calling upon governments, international
financial institutions and corporations to renew their commitments
to women's economic status in the face of new constraints and
opportunities posed by globalization," Heyzer added.
</P>
<P>
UNIFEM is the women's fund at the United Nations that provides
financial support and technical assistance to innovative programs
promoting women's human rights, their economic and political
empowerment and gender equality.
</P>
<P>
 UNIFEM advocates within the U.N. system to link women's
interests and concerns to all critical issues on the national,
regional and global agenda.
</P>
<P>
Created in 1976 as an innovative and catalytic fund, UNIFEM
has 12 Regional Program Directors, and a growing network of
affiliated gender advisors and specialists in Asia and the Pacific,
Western Asia, Africa, Latin America and the Caribbean, and the
Central and Eastern Europe and the Commonwealth of Independent
States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
