<HEADLINE> Russian Parliament OKs Peacekeeping Bill on Sierra-Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Federation Council, the
upper house of the parliament, Wednesday approved a bill on
dispatching 115 Russian armymen to Sierra- Leone as part of U.N.
peacekeeping troops in the African country.
</P>
<P>
The bill was initiated by Russian President Vladimir Putin at
the request of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
A resolution passed by the upper chamber of the Russian
parliament says that one aviation formation would be sent to
Sierra-Leone, including four Mi-24 helicopter gunships with
requisite weaponry,ammunition and other military hardware. The
maximum size of the Russian military formation would be 115 people.
</P>
<P>
The Russian contingent will operate as part of the U.N.
peacekeeping force in the area chosen by the U.N. Security Council.
Its main tasks will be to guarantee the security of the U.N.
personnel"through air escort of ground convoys, search and rescue
flights,support for air-borne operations, patrol and monitoring
flights," says the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the contingent will be set by August 7. If
necessary, its term will be extended by the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
