<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Guo Jianhua, Defender of Human Rights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- An elderly Chinese man, wrongly
jailed for nine years during the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976),
was in the Great Hall of the People today to discuss juvenile
crime prevention with the country's legislators.
</P>
<P>
The 65-year-old Guo Jianhua is now the head of Dongzhou
Children's Village in Sanyuan County, northwest China's Shaanxi
province.
</P>
<P>
The village, built by Guo and his brother four years ago with
an investment of 500,000 yuan, is China's first non-government
charitable cause set up specially for children behind bars. Now it
accommodates 48 children, ranging in age from 5 to 16.
</P>
<P>
"Despite crimes committed by their parents, the children are
innocent," Guo said. "The children should also enjoy the rights to
life, education and care."
</P>
<P>
Today's symposium was the first large-scale juvenile crime
prevention meeting since the passage of the juvenile crime
prevention law in June 1999. China now has 370 million juveniles.
</P>
<P>
Guo was imprisoned for committing "counter-revolutionary crimes
" during the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Guo declined a government post after his rehabilitation and
instead returned to his poor home village in Dongzhou. After years
of dedicated work, Guo has turned Dongzhou into an affluent
village, where per capita income reached nearly 6,000 yuan last
year.
</P>
<P>
"Reform and opening up made our village richer," said Guo, who
was given the honorary title of "outstanding township entrepreneur
" some years ago. "I hope to repay society and help the children
grow into healthy young adults."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Guo Jianhua, Defender of Human Rights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After their parents have signed custody agreements with village
administrators, juveniles can stay in the village until they reach
age 16, and will be provided with free accommodation, health care,
and schooling. Measures will also be taken to guarantee the
legitimate rights and interests of the children, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
Five-year-old Xiao Yan has lived in the village for some time.
Before her arrival, her father was jailed for accidentally killing
her mother. He attempted suicide several times. But the once-
desperate man has regained his optimism.
</P>
<P>
Statistics suggest that about 98 percent of those jailed were
granted leniency for their good behavior in the village.
</P>
<P>
The village plays a significant role in protecting the
legitimate rights and interests of special social groups and
preventing juvenile crimes, said experts.
</P>
<P>
"This is the second time that I came to the Great Hall of the
People," Guo said. His last visit to the hall was in the summer of
1992 when he was cited by the central government for helping the
poor to lead a better life.
</P>
<P>
Guo returned to the Great Hall of the People today as an
outstanding representative who defends the human rights of the
jailed and their children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
