<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Chief Shrugs Off Iranian Defector's Story on Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Director General of Turkish Police
Turan Genc dismissed on Wednesday a coined story of Iranian link to
the Pan Am Lockerbie bombing in 1988, reported the Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Genc said that "Sayyid Behbahani is not a very important
person." "He told us that he worked for the Iranian intelligence
organization for some time, but he didn't tell any important thing
except that. The issue will be solved from now on," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States CBS television aired in its "60 Minutes"
program on Sunday that an Iranian named Ahmad Behbahani, who is
currently in Turkey, claimed that he has evidence that it was Iran
that planned and financed the Lockerbie bombing, which killed 270
people.
</P>
<P>
The bombshell touched off a huge uproar in the local press. But
the Turkish National Intelligence Organization (MIT) poured cold
water on the agitation saying in a statement on Monday that
Behbahani's allegations have to be verified.
</P>
<P>
MIT underlined that the circumstances surrounding the Behbahani
case were very dubious. "We are adopting a cautious policy in order
not to create speculation and provocations both in Turkey and
abroad," it added.
</P>
<P>
Genc told reporters that Behbahani entered Turkey's Baskale
township of eastern Van province adjacent to Iran in March and he
was questioned in Van and sent to a Guest House in the Refugee Camp
in Yozgat, central Turkey.
</P>
<P>
There was nothing important in his statements and the MIT was
questioning him, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the CBS story that its reporter visited and
interviewed the Iranian national, Genc said that "those who come to
the refugee camp are interviewed before settling in the camp. They
can visit the city and come back on permission. The guest house is
just like a hotel."
</P>
<P>
"But persons whose conditions are serious can't be permitted to
leave the guest house. Behbahani was not permitted to leave the
place. Even the American CBS television wanted to make interview
with him, but we didn't permit that," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Prefers Exporting Products Instead of Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government reassured
overseas Filipino workers (OFWs) Wednesday that it will continue
to pursue long-term measures that would allow them to stay home
and seek job opportunities here instead of going abroad.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Jose Pardo of the Department of Finance said this is
one reason why government is concentrating on building up its
advantage in the electronics and exports sectors.
</P>
<P>
"We would not want really just pure exportation of labor
because it has social costs and other problems that it creates. We
would rather hope that they use the Philippines as a production
center," Pardo said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
The government's reassurance coincided with the observance of
Migrant Workers' Day on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Pardo also said the government continues to pursue measures
and benefits for the OFWs, who he said make great contributions to
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Pardo said President Joseph Estrada is thankful to the OFW
sector for their remittances that keep the Philippine economy
afloat year after year.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from his department, he said some seven million
OFWs in different parts of the world remit 7 billion U.S. dollars
every year to the economy.
</P>
<P>
Pardo noted that the president has not forgotten his commitment
to attract investments into the country so the Philippines would
be exporting world-class products instead of labor.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government wants the OFWs to be part of the
bustling electronics industry, which forms the bulk of Philippine
exports.
</P>
<P>
Filipino workers, according to Pardo, are best suited for this
industry because of their high-skill levels and comprehension of
English. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
