<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Sri Lanka's War Heroes Day Marred by Bloody Bombing  By Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankans on Wednesday were
holding procession to mark the country's first ever War Heroes Day
when a suicide bomber detonated himself to assassinate a hard-line
cabinet minister leading the parade.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industrial Development C. V. Gunaratne and 21
others were killed instantly in the bombing at Ratmalana in
southern suburb of Colombo, which was blamed on separatist rebels
of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
Gunaratne, 65, is the first senior government official to be
assassinated by LTTE rebels since the People's Alliance government
led by President Chandrika Kumaratunga was elected to office in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Police said the bombing happened at 1:45 p.m. local time (0745
GMT) when the minister was leading a procession in his electorate
to commemorate the War Heroes Day which fell on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One eyewitness said he saw a man approach the minister as he
walked in front of the parade. The bomber then embraced the
minister before setting off the bomb.
</P>
<P>
Body parts and shattered glass covered the blast site, one
kilometer from the Ratmalana airport which is used by the air
force. Police quickly cordoned off the area and reinforcements
were sent in.
</P>
<P>
At least 60 people including the minister's wife were injured,
15 of them seriously, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
Many vehicles were also damaged in the blast.
</P>
<P>
The procession, which set off from the southern suburb of Mount
Lavinia, was on its way to the southern town of Panadura, 25 km
south of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The state Lakhanda radio said the procession was part of a fund
raising campaign to improve the welfare of thousands of government
soldiers and their families.
</P>
<P>
Gunaratne attended the main ceremony held Wednesday morning at
the President's Secretariat here to mark the War Heroes Day.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the ceremony he drove away to his constituency in
the suburban Dehiwala to take part in the march as a mark of
respect to the security forces who fight the LTTE rebels in the
northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, who have been fighting for 17 years to carve
out a homeland for minority Tamils, are known for setting off
explosions that target government officials.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said Wednesday's attack was not totally
unexpected as the police recently discovered a large haul of
explosives and weapons, including a "suicide jacket" commonly used
by the LTTE, hidden in a cricket bag and buried north of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Gunaratne was the key minister who had been advocating the need
to put the country on a war footing since 1996 and the government,
with the escalation of the war, put the country on a war footing
on May 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan government had declared the June 7 as the War Heroes
Day which was designed to bolster morale among troops in the
northernmost Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Government forces have been fighting to stop LTTE rebels taking
the key northern town of Jaffna after the rebels launched an
offensive in April.
</P>
<P>
A countrywide two-minute silence was observed Wednesday morning
followed by the address to nation by the president, who thanked
the families of soldiers who had died in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
"Let us bow our heads in homage to those who are making the
supreme sacrifice, so that you and I may live in comfort and peace,
" she said.
</P>
<P>
She also said that she believed there could be no military
solution to the long-running conflict with the LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to reiterate that our cherished dream of peace can be
achieved only through a political solution of giving space for
every citizen of this country to live in dignity and harmony," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The president said her government was working towards bringing
in a new constitution. It has proposed to devolve powers to
regions, including one run by Tamils, in an effort to share power
with the minorities who accuse the majority Sinhalese of
discrimination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
