<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Managing Risks of Globalization -- Key Task for Asia: ESCAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) ended its 56th
annual meeting here Wednesday with all the members agreeing that
the overarching challenge facing the region is to manage the risks
and seize the opportunities of globalization.
</P>
<P>
With development through globalization and partnership in the
21st century as its theme, the commission noted that the
irreversible nature of globalization and interdependence requires
continuous national capacity building for all the countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The commission reaffirmed its strong commitment to a rule-based
multilateral trading system that operates in a non-discriminatory
and transparent manner and that ensures predictable and secure
market access.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the World Trade Organization (WTO) is of
paramount importance to the expansion of trade, continued economic
prosperity and all-round balanced development.
</P>
<P>
However, as a lot of developing countries in the ESCAP region
are not yet members of the WTO, the secretariat was asked to give
high priority to its technical assistance and advisory services to
enable these countries to integrate into the world economy.
</P>
<P>
With a nod toward strengthening its sub-regional programs, the
commission proclaimed 2000-2009 as the Decade of Greater Mekong
Subregion Development Cooperation to draw attention and encourage
support of the international community to intensify economic and
social development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The commission has been asked to mobilize the necessary
measures to provide technical assistance to the Greater Mekong
Subregion, particularly on such key sectors as human resources
development, trade and investment, transportation and
communication, poverty alleviation and social development.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP also underlined its support for phase two of the regional
space applications program for sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Space technology and its applications, it noted, are important
for vital areas from food security and agricultural systems to
natural disaster reduction, health care and hygiene.
</P>
<P>
Human resources development is also considered a key issue for
alleviating poverty, especially for the enhancement of educational,
health and employment status in marginalized population groups.
</P>
<P>
The commission resolved to focus on investments in all areas of
human resources development, including education and training,
health and nutrition and sustainable livelihood.
</P>
<P>
During this first session in the new millennium, lasting from
June 1 to June 7, ESCAP welcomed Georgia as its 52nd member and
said farewell to its outgoing Executive Secretary Adrianus Mooy of
Indonesia. Kim Hak-Su from South Korea will take over as ESCAP's
new executive secretary on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
