<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Meet on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
met here on Wednesday morning to be briefed by the U.N.
Secretariat on the latest developments in Sierra Leone, where
government army clashed with rebels overnight near the northern
town of Kabala.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came as the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
was reported to have told the United Nations that they would
release 21 Indian peacekeepers they were holding very soon.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Mission in Sierra Leone (UNAMSIL) Tuesday
reported that the RUF rebels had transferred more than 20 U.N.
peacekeepers to an unknown destination.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, told a press conference
Tuesday here that 21 of the 23 Indian peacekeepers, who had been
surrounded by the RUF in eastern town of Kuiva in Sierra Leone,
were transferred overnight to an unknown location by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the movement of the 21 personnel
could follow the same pattern as that of other peacekeepers, who
have been released first through Foya in Liberia and then to
Monrovia, the Liberian capital.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Eckhard said that U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan had emphasized in a telephone call to Liberian
President Charles Taylor Tuesday that all restrictions on the
movement of U.N. personnel must be lifted and that anyone who
mistreated peacekeepers would be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
The call to President Taylor, who was entrusted by the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) to take the
lead in obtaining the release of all detainees, underscored that
the job to end the detainee situation through diplomacy had not
been completed simply because U.N. personnel did not enjoy the
freedom of movement in the country.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in Sierra Leone resumed in May when rebels took
hostage hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers, killed several more and
started marching towards the nation's capital of Freetown in
defiance of the July 1999 peace accord, under which the United
Nations can play a role in monitoring the peace process in the
West African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
