<HEADLINE> Namibian President Denies Possessing Diamond Mine in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam Nujoma
vehemently denied Wednesday a local newspaper report that he owns
a diamond mine in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) where
his troops are helping the government quell a rebellion, according
to South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued on Nujoma's behalf signed by acting Minister
of Foreign Affairs, Tuliameni Kalomoh, said the report in the
Windhoek Observer was "utterly false".
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report on Saturday alleged that Nujoma owned a
diamond mine at Maji-Munene, 45 km from the town of Tshikapa in
central DRC.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, which also published photographs of the mine,
claimed the operation was being run by members of Namibia Defence
Force.
</P>
<P>
Kalomoh said: "President Nujoma has denied the allegation with
contempt."
</P>
<P>
"The government of Namibia has stated time and time again that
our decision to send to troops to the DRC was not motivated by any
economic considerations," he added.
</P>
<P>
His statement also defended that the presence of Namibian
troops in the DRC had "created the necessary conditions for the
deployment of UN peacekeeping force in the Congo and allowing the
Congolese people to find a lasting political solution through the
democratic process".
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Namibia has sent troops, believed to
number about 2, 000, to help DRC President Laurent Kabila in his
fight against rebel groups backed by Rwanda and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
