<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Business Confidence Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The South African Chamber of
Business' (SACOB's) Business Confidence Index fell five points in
May, the largest drop this year and the fourth consecutive monthly
fall, SACOB chief executive officer Kevin Wakeford said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a media briefing here, Wakeford said the index has
been negatively affected by lower import volumes, the average U.S.
dollar gold price declining, headline inflation being up to 4.5
percent as well as the rand reaching a new low against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Wakeford said SACOB has called on the South African Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel, in conjunction with the Reserve Bank, to
urgently review inflation targets.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank governor Tito Mboweni recently stressed his
determination to fulfil his constitutional mandate to meet the
three to six percent inflation target by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
The chamber disagreed that the current range of three to six
percent is attainable, advising that a band of five to eight
percent should be set as a realistic target.
</P>
<P>
Wakeford added that the May 10 general strike against job
losses led by the Congress of South African Trade Union also
impacted on the business confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
