<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundians in Camps to Be Release by End of July: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Burundians interned in
controversial regroupment camps will be released by July 31,
former South African president and chief mediator for the troubled
Great Lakes country Nelson Mandela and Burundi President Pierre
Buyoya agreed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also reached consensus that Burundi's troops
should be integrated on a half-to-half basis to include Tutsi and
opposing Hutu factions.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Buyoya also discussed the release of political
prisoners, some of whom have been held for seven years without
trial.
</P>
<P>
Although they did not reach a conclusion on this matter, the
two leaders agreed this issue will be discussed again when Mandela
visits Burundi next week.
</P>
<P>
"For people like us who spent 27 years in prison it is
difficult to remain calm when discussing prisoners and having
people in regroupment camps," said Mandela, adding that it has
taken a great deal of courage on Buyoya's part to reach
Wednesday's decisions.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela stressed that all agreements made at the
meeting at his residence will still have to be endorsed by
Burundi's cabinet, national assembly, judiciary, religious leaders
and the rank and file of the population.
</P>
<P>
On the controversial issue of a ceasefire between the
Tutsi-dominated government army and the mainly Hutu rebels,
Mandela said he has warned Burundian generals at the meeting not
to be in too much of a hurry.
</P>
<P>
"I told them about our experience in this country and that of
the Irish Republican Army. We said we will not sign a ceasefire
until we are convinced that the process is irreversible. A
ceasefire before a settlement is something impossible," he added,
warning that if the ceasefire accord is signed too soon, the
rebels will not agree to the peace process which takes its next
round in the Tanzanian town of Arusha in July.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya said he has asked Mandela to request the rebels to
"cease attacking the population" while the regroupment camps will
be in the process of being dismantled.
</P>
<P>
"That is something very reasonable," responded Mandela, saying
he believed that the rebels will agree to a ceasefire at Arusha.
</P>
<P>
On the integration of the Burundian military, Mandela said the
rebels had previously wanted a 75 percent Hutu majority.
</P>
<P>
"But I persuaded them against that. It will never work. The
proper way to start is 50-50," he said.
</P>
<P>
At least 200,000 people, both Hutus and Tutsis, have been
killed since October 1993 when the conflict between Tutsi-led
government troops and Hutu rebels broke out.
</P>
<P>
Peace efforts have dragged on for two years with violence
continuing on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Hutus represent 85 percent of Burundi's population, who are
mostly peasant farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Next Parliament Must Solve Land Issue: Zimbabwean President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Wednesday said that the next parliament must take bold measures
to solve the land issue.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe was addressing the ruling Zimbabwe African National
Union- Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) parliamentary candidates at a
pre-election parliamentary caucus in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said the economic progress in Zimbabwe was based on the
ownership and possession of land.
</P>
<P>
He said the revolutionary struggle to liberate the country was
not finished until land was given to the people.
</P>
<P>
"The next parliament must be a parliament to conclude this last
part of our revolution to own our resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said in addition to the 804 farms that were gazetted for
acquisition, the government would look for more to add to the
list.
</P>
<P>
He said if Britain and the United States had not reneged on
their promise to fund land reform, the process would have been
concluded a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
War veterans of the 1970s liberation struggle for independence
from Britain started occupying white-owned commercial farms in
February this year, saying they wanted arable land.
</P>
<P>
The land issue generated interest throughout the world with
Britain and other European countries condemning Mugabe while
African leaders supported him.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the government would only have formidable economic
policies if resources were owned by the majority.
</P>
<P>
He said it was surprising that issues such as high inflation
and interest rates were being blamed on the government when in
actual fact they were created by the minority who owned the
resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
