<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Receives No Request for Arrest of Cote d'Ivoire Ex-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- France said Wednesday it has received
no request from the judicial authority of Cote d'Ivoire for
arresting Henri Konan Bedie, former president of the country who
is living in exile in France.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman for the French Foreign Ministry Anne Gazeau-Secret
said the French embassy in Abidjan has been asked by Cote d'Ivoire
authorities to cooperate with four rogatory judicial commissions
in charge of investigating the alleged embezzlement of public fund
by Bedie as well as his family members and top aides.
</P>
<P>
"But our embassy in Abidjan has not received so far
confirmation relative to an international arrest warrant," she
said without giving more opinion on the decision by the military
junta of Cote d'Ivoire to prosecute Bedie.
</P>
<P>
France and Cote d'Ivoire have a bilateral agreement on judicial
cooperation which was signed in 1961.
</P>
<P>
Bedie and his entourage went into exile in France after a coup
was staged by General Robert Guei on December 24, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The junta has launched "an operation of clean hands" and
accused Bedie, former Prime Minister Daniel Kablan Duncan, and
former Finance Minister Niamien N'Goran of embezzlement of public
fund.
</P>
<P>
The General Prosecutor of Cote d'Ivoire issued an international
arrest warrant for them Tuesday, but he did not ask France to
extradite these men.
</P>
<P>
Local observers said France is not enthusiastic to cooperate
with Cote d'Ivoire over the affair, which Paris considers as an
internal problem connected with the next presidential election in
the country.
</P>
<P>
An extradition of Bedie will also mean that France will lose
its reputation as a country of exile for former African heads of
state or government who are toppled in coups or internal turmoil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
