<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Assistance Urged for Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Atomic Forum (FORATOM)
Wednesday urged more international assistance for Ukraine that is
closing down its Chernobyl nuclear power plant by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The forum, the trade association of the European nuclear
industry, said that with the closure date for Chernobyl now set,
the international community must now do its utmost to help Ukraine
tackle the resulting problems.
</P>
<P>
The problems are expected to emerge from the country's loss of
generating capacity. At present, almost 44 percent of the former
Soviet republic's electric power is nuclear-generated.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to the loss of generating capacity resulting from
the Chernobyl closure, there is the threat of large-scale job
losses that could easily worsen Ukraine's existing socio-economic
problems," said the FORATOM in a written statement issued after
Ukraine announced its plan to shut down the Chernobyl nuclear
power station on December 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine had pledged to close Chernobyl, where the world's worst
nuclear accident occurred 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine is fulfilling its pledge to close Chernobyl. Given the
pressing need for economic improvement in the region, the
international community is under an obligation to help minimize
the impact that the Chernobyl closure will have on Ukraine," said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has so far provided Ukraine with 100
million euros (94 million U.S. dollars) as the Chernobyl shelter
fund. Closure of the power plant was among conditions for the
release of another 92 million euros (86 million dollars) as macro-
economic assistance from the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The FORATOM has promised Ukraine 1.5 billion dollars in loan as
part of a global package involving the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development and other donors as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
