<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Premier Calls For Further Development of Sino-Japanese Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Vice Premier Qian
Qichen Wednesday called for the further development of Sino-
Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here early in the day to attend the official
funeral of former Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi scheduled
on June 8 as special envoy of the Chinese government, made the
call during a meeting with Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono.
</P>
<P>
Qian expounded the Chinese government's policy which attaches
importance to the development of Sino-Japanese ties, and stressed
that the two sides should maintain the current momentum of
bilateral ties and actively promote the two countries' friendly
cooperative partnership devoted to peace and development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier also explained to Kono the Chinese
government stance on the Taiwan issue, and expressed the hope that
the Japanese side would abide by the principles and spirits set
forth in the "China-Japan Joint Statement" and "China-Japan Joint
Declaration," and handle issues related to Taiwan properly.
</P>
<P>
Kono said the Japanese side is satisfied with the smooth
development of bilateral ties and vowed to make unremitting
efforts for the enhancement of such relations.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides also exchanged views on
strengthening and expanding the two countries' friendly
cooperation in various fields, and reached consensus on many
issues. 
