<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polluted Lake Water Drained in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Huizhou city in south China's
Guangdong Province started today to drain polluted water from West
Lake and replace it with clean water from a nearby reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The lake has the same name as the more famous West Lake in
Zhejiang Province, known nationally for its scenic beauty and many
historical spots.
</P>
<P>
Huizhou's West Lake is 1,600 years old as a tourist resort.
Urbanization has contributed to the lake pollution, with some one
million tons of sewage discharged into it every year.
</P>
<P>
The city government said it will take 20 days to drain the 1.5
million cu m of silt-filled water from the lake, before the
reservoir water can be channeled in.
</P>
<P>
The city government has invested 12 million yuan (1.4 million
US dollars) this year to build an underground pipeline for the
drainage project.
</P>
<P>
The work should be finished by the end of this month, and is
expected to substantially change the appearance of the lake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
