<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Not to Attend ECO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- President Ahmet Necdet Sezer will not
attend the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) summit scheduled
on June 10 in the Iranian capital of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a statement on Wednesday that the
president can not attend the sixth ECO summit due to his "intense
work" in early days of his term in office.
</P>
<P>
It said Turkey attaches special importance to the ECO which has
constructive functions in globalization process, and State Minister
Mehmet Kececiler will represent Turkey at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after Iranian President Muhammad Khatami
on Monday sent Deputy Foreign Mohammad Hossein Adeli to Ankara as
his special envoy to invite Sezer to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The ECO was founded by Iran, Turkey and Pakistan in 1985. It was
joined by Afghanistan and the Central Asian and Caucasian republics
of Azerbaijan, Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan and
Kazakhstan after the collapse of former Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after he took office on May 16, Sezer declared that he
would not take part in the forthcoming summit. But both Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem reportedly
advised him to change his mind, because the summit has "great
significance for Turkey in terms of regional politics."
</P>
<P>
Iran and Turkey have long been cool toward each other. Recently
their relations were marred by media accusation that Iran had been
involved in the murder of famous Turkish intellectuals. Tehran
denied the charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Offers International Bid for Construction of High-Speed Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has started the process of
calling international tenders for the construction of a high-speed
railway to link Alexandria on the Mediterranean coast and the
southern town of Aswan, Transport Ministry spokesman said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is studying the terms of the tenders, which will be
up for bidding in December, Hassan Salah was quoted as saying by
the country's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The contract, which is being drafted with the help of an unnamed
Spanish company, is estimated to be worth around 10 billion
Egyptian pounds (2.85 billion U.S. dollars), Salah said.
</P>
<P>
Spain has agreed to help Egypt finish an evaluation of the
viability for the project to traverse almost the entire length of
the country and to cover part of the project fund in loans.
</P>
<P>
Salah said the first phase of 200 kilometers between Alexandria
and Cairo will take two years to complete at a cost of 4 billion
pounds (1.14 billion dollars). The final two stages will take
another three years to build, ending in the tourist resort of
Aswan, about 700 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The railway will follow the course of the Nile River valley and
pass through major tourist destinations including Luxor, the site
of pharaonic temples and tombs.
</P>
<P>
The current Alexandria-Aswan railway line, which will remain
intact, are in poorly maintenance and runs slow trains. The new
trains will travel at a speed of up to 300 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
Transport Minister Ibrahim el-Demiri was quoted in Tuesday's
business daily Al-Alam Al-Yom as saying that the new railway will
provide a more secure and faster train transport for tourists.
Tourism is one of the four biggest foreign exchange earners for
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's state-owned railway, which runs 7,000 kilometers,
carries about 1 billion passengers a year and has received 11
billion pounds (3.14 billion dollars) in government subsidies since
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
