<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Refuses Foreign Interference on Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government ruled out
Wednesday any foreign interference in the ultimate solution of the
Sulu hostage crisis even in the event talks with the Abu Sayyaf
collapse.
</P>
<P>
"We will tell them to hold the line and not to interfere with
our negotiations. It will just make it harder for everybody,"
chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado made this remark in response to the reported foreign
interference relevant to monetary demands presented by the Abu
Sayyaf in exchange for the release of the 21 mostly foreign
captives who have been held in Sulu province since April 23.
</P>
<P>
He said the government negotiating team is at present in the
process of scrutinizing the viability of the counter-proposal
presented by the Abu Sayyaf following the government's resistance
to their three self-imposed demands.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippine government is keen on yielding to the
Abu Sayyaf's desire to hasten development of fishing industry in
Basilan, Tawi-Tawi and Sulu waters thus upholding its legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
The other two demands, the creations of an independent Islamic
state and a Sabah Commission, remain on status quo as the
government refuses to deal with demands beyond constitutional
limitations.
</P>
<P>
Press Undersecretary Mike Toledo, for his part, said the
government is hopeful that negotiations for the safe release of
the 21 hostages will resume Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government remains committed to fulfill President Joseph
Estrada's order to seek the safe release of the hostages, Toledo
added.
</P>
<P>
Gvernment panelists led by Aventajado held formal talks with
the Abu Sayyaf on May 27 but failed to secure the release of the
hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Legislative Passes Bill on Niger Delta Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Senate has endorsed with a
two-thirds majority the long-delayed Niger Delta Development
Commission (NDDC) bill, overriding president rejection.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's voting confirmed an earlier approval of the bill by
the House of Representatives, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo, objecting to some of the revises
made to the bill, had declined to sign and returned it to the
National Assembly after the House's approval.
</P>
<P>
The NDDC bill and bill for the current anti-corruption act were
 submitted by Obasanjo administration immediately after its
inauguration on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Niger delta region, which accounts for about 90 percent of
oil production in Nigeria, the largest oil-exporting country in
Africa, is among the poorest areas in the country due to decades
of neglect by the northerner-dominated military regimes and
exploitation by the foreign oil firms.
</P>
<P>
The bill is designed to tackle the problems by setting up a new
 governmental body pooling efforts and resources at federal, state
and corporate levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
