<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Calls for Judicial Exchanges With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye on Wednesday urged the judicial institutions in
Tanzania and China to enhance bilateral exchanges and strengthen
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a visiting delegation of the Chinese People's
Supreme Court led the court's Vice-President Zhu Mingshan, the
Tanzanian prime minister said although the two countries have
different judicial systems, judicial institutions in the two
countries should learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
"This visit should be the beginning of many visits in this
important sector, " said Sumaye.
</P>
<P>
He told the Chinese delegation, which also includes presidents
of the High Court of China's western Gansu Province and the
Military Court of the People's Liberation Army, that Tanzania
valued the long-term friendly relationship between the two
countries and insisted on the "one China" policy over the Taiwan
issue.
</P>
<P>
China has achieved a great success in the building of market
economy and Tanzania wants to learn from China in the field, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told the Tanzanian prime minister that China is trying to
build a socialist democratic judicial system in conformity with
the market economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very important part of the political reform in China,"
Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the delegation met with the Tanzanian Chief Justice
Barnabas Samata.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation arrived here last Friday for a five-day
visit. Tanzania is the second stop of their two-week African tour
of Algeria, Tanzania and Morocco. 
</P>
