<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Outlaw Sexual Harassment at Workplace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission Wednesday
adopted a directive to ban sexual harassment at workplace.
</P>
<P>
Sexual harassment "is an unacceptable affront to the
individual concerned, normally -- but not always -- a woman," EU
social policy commissioner Anna Diamantopoulou said.
</P>
<P>
She added that very few legal systems had yet got to grip with
the notion of sexual harassment and it is partly attributable to
the inherent difficulty in defining it.
</P>
<P>
"But this should not deter us from our duty to send the
strongest possible signal that sexual harassment must be outlawed
from the workplace," said the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The commission directive, to be transformed into national
regulation or legislation by EU member states, considered that
sexual harassment is a form of sexual discrimination and thus
entails a risk of liability for employers who fail to provide a
workplace free of harassment.
</P>
<P>
Diamantopoulou said the main purpose of the commission
directive is preventive. "By establishing a community framework
for sexual harassment, we draw attention to the problem throughout
Europe and create momentum among employers to take their own steps
to stamp it out," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
