<HEADLINE> Russian, Finnish Presidents Pledge to Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We agreed that we must treat with care what were achieved in
relations between the former USSR, then Russia and Finland. It is
a good base for the development of our future relations," Putin
told the press following his one-on-one talks with Halonen at the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed a wide range of issues at the meeting,
particularly bilateral economic and border cooperation and
development of the customs infrastructure at the Russian-Finnish
border, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
The presidents also talked over the coordination of the two
countries' efforts in international organizations, international
security and cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Finland's position in international organizations is important
" for Russia, stressed Putin.
</P>
<P>
He declared that there are no territorial questions or disputes
between Russia and Finland, because "the question is settled and
closed completely in the sphere of international law."
</P>
<P>
Putin noted that debates on territorial claims are very
dangerous and capable of destroying the existing ties between the
two countries which "should develop their relationship and look
into the future."
</P>
<P>
For her part, Halonen said that the standard of bilateral ties
permits the discussion of any matters. "I also respect the work
done by our predecessors. And we, as practical people, have tried
to resolve questions that can be solved today," she said.
</P>
<P>
After the presidents' talks, the full delegations opened full-
scale negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Putin told the guests that Russia cherishes its relations with
Finland and attaches great significance to them.
</P>
<P>
Halonen, who arrived here Tuesday evening for a two-day working
visit, said she hopes to expand cooperation with Russia on the
basis of equality and mutual benefit. 
</P>
