<HEADLINE> Trial of World Athletics Championships Distrupter Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Trial of a group of 10 people who
posed as mascots and held up signs supporting Basque separatists
during the opening ceremony of last year's world athletics
championships in Seville, Spain, began in Seville on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a bold manner, the eight men and two women embarrassed the
organizers who, fearing possible attacks by the armed Basque
separatist group ETA, had considerably tightened security.
</P>
<P>
The group entered the Seville stadium on August 20 with tickets
bought for the opening ceremony. After the ceremony got started,
two of the protesters donned fake mascot outfits and slipped onto
the main stage. They held pro-ETA banners and danced for about 20
minutes in front of an international television audience. Others
in the group also held banners.
</P>
<P>
The protesters are charged with disrupting public order and
prosecutors are seeking fines of 730,000 pesetas (4,700 U.S.
dollars) for each of them.
</P>
<P>
They also are seeking a one-year prison sentence for one of the
protesters who allegedly bit a police agent while being detained
during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
All 10 group members were released two days after the ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
