<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Pipes Drinking Water from Distant River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Water from the Dongjiang River was
channeled through a 56.3-km-long pipe to the special economic zone
of Shenzhen today to ease the drinking water shortage.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the pipeline, which started in 1996, cost 1.67
billion yuan (about 200 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The project will supply Shenzhen with 350 million cu m of high
quality water from the upper stream of the river every year.
</P>
<P>
At today's test run of the system, the water flowed at 11 cu m
per second through the airtight pipe.
</P>
<P>
The system is operated through an advanced remote-control
program.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, a fast growing modern coastal city in south China,
has no river source of its own, and is expected to have a
shortfall of some one billion cu m of water by the year 2010 if
nothing has been done to preserve rainfall or channel water from
other sources, according to experts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
