<HEADLINE> China, Moldova Issue Joint Statement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Republic of China (PRC)
and the Republic of Moldova here today issued a joint statement on
continuously enhancing all-round cooperation in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and visiting Moldova President
Petru Lucinschi signed the joint statement.
</P>
<P>
To further promote the China-Moldova cooperative relations in
all fields, the agreement says, both sides firmly believe the
necessity to further develop and deepen the friendly relations
between the two countries and two peoples in accordance with the
purposes and principles of the U.N. Charter and other
international laws on the basis of mutual respect of sovereignty,
territorial integrity and noninterference of internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also reaffirm their observance of the joint
communique between the two countries signed on November 7, 1992.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, both sides consider that the world
is seeing profound changes, fully demonstrating the trends of
multi-polarization and economic globalization and increasing the
interdependence of all countries.
</P>
<P>
It says that all countries, big or small, strong or weak, rich
or poor, should have the rights to determine their own fate and
enjoy equal rights to participate in discussion and resolve
international issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
