<HEADLINE> China to Further Implement Law on Juvenile Delinquency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China will take a firmer hand in
the enforcement of the Law on Juvenile Delinquency, in a bid to
raise awareness of the law among young people and to protect their
rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at a three-day symposium on
implementing the law, which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, sponsored by the National People's Congress (NPC)
Committee for Internal and Judicial Affairs and the Central
Committee of the Communist Youth League of China (CYLC), was held
on the eve of the first anniversary of the law's approval, which
was June 28, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Wan Chaofen, vice-chairwoman of the NPC Committee for Internal
and Judicial Affairs, called on departments concerned to intensify
legal education among China's juveniles, and combine the job of
curbing juvenile delinquency with the work of protecting their
rights.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Qiang, first secretary of the CYLC Central Committee, said
in his speech that the CYLC, as the bridge between the Communist
Party of China and the Chinese younger generation, is responsible
for promoting the law.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from seven central government departments and
representatives from 16 provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions aired their views during the past three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
