<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Approves Early Election in Preliminary Reading EDS-2nd lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset (Parliament)
Wednesday passed a motion proposed by opposition parties to hold
early elections in a preliminary reading, an event that may hamper
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's efforts to push forward the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The motion, submitted by Knesset member Avigdor Lieberman from
National Union-Yisrael Beiteinu and Silvan Shalom from the major
opposition Likud party, was approved by a vote of 61-48, with
eleven Knesset members failing to show up on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
The bill, calling for dissolving the Knesset and holding
elections within 90 days, only needs a simple majority in the 120-
seat Knesset in Wednesday's preliminary reading. It must be
reviewed by the Knesset Law Committee and go through three more
readings, during which at least 61 votes are required.
</P>
<P>
Several ruling partners of Barak's coalition government,
including the ultra-Orthodox Shas party who holds 17 seats in the
Knesset, voted along with the oppositions in Wednesday's
parliamentary showdown.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, officials in Barak's office spread news that
Barak and his confidants are trying to recruit Shinui Party,
Democratic List and Am Ehad into a new and narrow coalition,
according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
The radio also reported that Barak planned to impose the
Transition Law on any ministers who voted in favor of early
elections, which means that they will be kicked out of the
government within a week after the vote.
</P>
<P>
Should Barak finally decide to do so, he will remain in power as
the leader of a minority coalition, relying on the Arab parties for
his future survival in office, local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The coalition crisis deteriorated after the breakdown of talks
between Shas, the Finance Ministry and the Education Ministry over
the fund allocation to Shas' educational system.
</P>
<P>
Shas had threatened to support the early election bill if it
could not get millions of additional dollars for its corrupt and
nearly bankrupt religious school network.
</P>
<P>
Barak ordered to stop the talks on Monday, saying he will not
act under threats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yisrael Ba'aliya, another junior party in the
coalition with four Knesset seats, also supported the early
election bill in Wednesday's voting.
</P>
<P>
The party attributed its defection to its opposition to the "
large concessions" Barak reportedly made to the Palestinians during
the Israeli-Palestinian back-channel talks in Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
National Religious Party, who had announced it will leave the
government if Barak transfers three Arab villages near Jerusalem to
the Palestinians, also voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
Party leader Yitzhak Levy said his party wants to warn Barak
against his "apparent intentions" to concede a large part of the
West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
However, Health Minister and Shas party leader Shlomo Benizri
suggested that his party may change its mind in the subsequent
reading of the bill if Barak agrees to resume talks with Shas.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to topple the government," Benizri said. "No one
wants to go to early elections, and the ball is now back in the
prime minister's court. ... If he wants to sit down seriously and
solve the crisis, then he is welcome," he said.
</P>
<P>
If the bill calling for early elections does not pass the third
and final reading, any similar motion will be forbidden in the
Knesset for six months.
</P>
<P>
The domestic government crisis may tie Barak's hands on the
negotiation table with the Palestinians as the peace talks have
just entered the "moment of truth."
</P>
<P>
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright managed just
on Tuesday to move Israeli and Palestinian negotiators back to
Washington to resume talks during her ongoing Middle East tour,
which began on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The negotiating teams are aiming to resolve the thorny final-
status issues, such as the fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements,
the return of Palestinian refugees, border, water and security, and
reach a permanent accord by September 13, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
