<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Expects No Breakthrough for Syrian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Wednesday she does not expect any breakthroughs will
be made on the Syrian track of peace process during her meeting
here with Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh.
</P>
<P>
"I do not expect any breakthroughs," she told a press conference
after meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
However, she stressed the door is open on the Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria and Israel broke down last January due
to disputes over the return of the Golan Heights that the Jewish
state seized from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here earlier in the day after two days of
visits to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas, during which
she secured the resumption of the Palestinian-Israeli talks in the
U.S. next week and a meeting between Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton at the White House on June
14.
</P>
<P>
Shareh is in Cairo for Arab foreign ministers meetings earlier
in the week. He told reporters on Tuesday that Syria must not fall
into the trap of "making unjustified concessions."
</P>
<P>
"To give Israel something that is ours or our right would not be
reassurance but a free and unwarranted concession. We must not fall
into such pitfalls," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, meanwhile, called on Syria to withdraw from Lebanon
after Israel pulled out of south Lebanon late last month, ending 22
years of occupation of a border strip in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
She praised Syria for having played a constructive and
cooperative role over Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
But she added it is "very important that all parties do in fact
follow through on their obligations. The Israelis have done so and
I think that the Syrians should do so also."
</P>
<P>
Syria stations more than 30,000 troops in Lebanon since 1976,
when it intervened to try to stop the Lebanese civil war.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria maintain that the situation is different
concerning the Syrian troops and Israel's: the Syrian troops are "
peacekeepers" while Israel's were occupation forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
