<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Official Refutes Stories About Iranian Defector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Huseyin Onal, governor of the Turkish
central province of Yozgat, said most of the news about the alleged
Iranian agent Sayyid Behbahani, who recently defected to Turkey,
were mere fabrications.
</P>
<P>
Onal made the remarks after Iran's intelligence chief dismissed
allegations by the so-called defector that Iran was behind the 1988
Lockerbie bombing, Turkish Daily News reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States' Columbia Broadcasting System (CBS) aired a
story recently, saying it had interviewed Behbahani who took refuge
in Yozgat refugee camp with a fake identification card.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, CBS said, the Iranian claimed himself to
be in charge of Iran's foreign terrorist activities and to have
plotted the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am plane over Lockerbie,
Scotland, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Onal said he has ordered an investigation into the refugee camp
and that it was impossible for anyone to enter the camp with a
false ID and talk to journalists.
</P>
<P>
However, while the U.S. Embassy in Ankara declined to comment on
the issue, Turkish National Intelligence Organization (MIT)
confirmed in an official statement that they had interrogated an
Iranian by that name, who illegally entered Turkey on March 7.
</P>
<P>
"Behbahani indicated that he had worked for a while in the
Iranian Intelligence Ministry, had been imprisoned in Evin Prison
after being indicted in 1998 for spying for a foreign country, and
had come to Turkey after fleeing from prison. He made contact with
a foreign news channel before coming to Turkey," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Behbahani, born in 1968 in Tehran and a high school graduate,
has asked for political asylum, the statement said, adding that he
has applied to the United Nations High Commission for Refugees to
go to the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The statement said he claimed that some terror activities in the
past were organized by Iran but has not given any indications that
Iran was involved in a series of political murders in Turkey in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The MIT said "all aspects of the subject are being investigated
by our organization. Until the allegations are verified, we are
adopting a cautious policy in order not to create speculation and
provocations both in Turkey and abroad."
</P>
<P>
Iran dismissed the Behbahani affair as a plot by the U.S. and
Israel, two of Tehran's arch foes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
