<HEADLINE> 2nd Lead: S.Lankan Minister Among 22 Killed in Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Police said the bombing happened at 1:45 p.m. (0745 GMT) at
Ratmalana in southern suburb of Colombo when the minister was
leading a procession in his electorate to commemorate the War
Heroes Day which fell on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One eyewitness said he saw a man approach the minister as he
walked in the parade in front of a big crowd. The bomber then
embraced the minister before setting off the bomb.
</P>
<P>
At least 60 people including the minister's wife were injured,
15 of them seriously, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
The state Lakhanda radio said the procession was part of a fund
raising campaign to improve the welfare of thousands of government
soldiers and their families.
</P>
<P>
Gunaratne is the first VIP to be assassinated by the rebels of
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) since the People Alliance
government led by President Chandrika Kumaratunga was elected to
office in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The government statement said Gunaratne attended the main
ceremony held Wednesday morning at the President's Secretariat to
mark the War Heroes Day.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the ceremony he drove away to his constituency in
the Colombo suburban Dehiwala to take part in the march to mark
the War Heroes Day as a mark of respect to the security forces who
fight the LTTE rebels in the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Government forces have been fighting to stop LTTE rebels taking
the key northern town of Jaffna after the rebels launched an
offensive in April.
</P>
<P>
Gunaratne was the key minister who had been advocating the need
to put the country on a war footing since 1996 and the government,
with the escalation of the war, put the country on a war footing
on May 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan government had declared the June 7 as the War Heroes
Day and a countrywide two minutes silence was observed Wednesday
morning followed by the address to nation by the president.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga made an address thanking the families of soldiers
who had died in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
"Let us bow our heads in homage to those who are making the
supreme sacrifice, so that you and I may live in comfort and peace,
" she said.
</P>
<P>
She also said she believed there could be no military solution
to the long-running conflict with the LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to reiterate that our cherished dream of peace can be
achieved only through a political solution of giving space for
every citizen of this country to live in dignity and harmony," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
