<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Sends Medical Team to Quake-Hit Bengkulu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Coordinating Minister
for the People's Welfare and Eradication of Poverty Basri
Hasanuddin Wednesday said the government has sent a medical team
and medical supplies to the quake-hit Bengkulu province.
</P>
<P>
He said the governors of 24 provinces have also added 240
million rupiah (30,000 U.S. dollars) to the humanitarian aid for
Bengkulu, 536 kilometers northwest of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Financial losses in Bengkulu were estimated at 100 billion
rupiah (12.5 million dollars), according to the provincial office
of the coordinating unit for natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Hasanuddin said some countries, such as Malaysia, Singapore,
the Netherlands, Switzerland, China, Thailand, the United States
and Australia have expressed their readiness to send assistance to
the province.
</P>
<P>
The assistance was made in response to the Indonesian
government's request for international aid, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency reported that heavy rain on Wednesday
hampered quake rescue efforts in the province where a strong
earthquake has killed 120 people and injured nearly 2,300 others.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain forced some residents to put aside those fears of
aftershocks and move into their damaged houses. Others stayed in
makeshift tents.
</P>
<P>
The rains and poor communications have postponed efforts to
reach Enggano island which lies close to the earthquake's
epicenter. Initial reports indicated no deaths had occurred on
Enggano, where most housing is simple huts.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of Sunday's earthquake, measuring 7.9 on the
Richter Scale, was located 112 kilometers from Bengkulu.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's far-flung islands are regularly hit by earthquakes.
At least 45 people died last month when an earthquake measuring 6.
5 on the Richter Scale hit Central Sulawesi and some neighboring
islands.
</P>
<P>
The worst quake to hit Indonesia in the past decade was in 1992,
when 2,200 people died in a string of eastern islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
