<HEADLINE> EU Acts to Reduce Commercial Flight Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Air travelers may still have to
suffer from delays at European airports during this summer's
vacationing frenzy but they could expect more punctual take-offs
and transits next year as the European Union is redressing the
annoyance.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, heard on Wednesday a special report on measures that can be
resorted to reduce commercial flight delays across the continent.
</P>
<P>
Loyola de Palacio, European transport commissioner, told the
commission of the first encouraging sign -- a confirmation of
support from all countries in the program aimed at reducing flight
delays and growing consensus of the need for integrated management
of European airspace.
</P>
<P>
The report was prepared by a special group of senior civil and
military representatives from different European countries who met
regularly since January this year to work out a proposal for
reform of air traffic management.
</P>
<P>
De Palacio, who chairs the high-level group, told the
commission that results should be achieved over the coming months.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, air travelers in Europe suffered from
delays of their flights and delays varied from scores of minutes
to hours. As many as one third of the scheduled flights had been
delayed for one reason or another during this period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
