<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments in Jordan's Stock Market Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investments in the Amman Stock
Exchange (ASE) declined sharply in the first five months of 2000 as
compared with the same period last year, bourse sources said here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Net foreign investments in the ASE in the period were 5.3
million dinars (7.4 million dollars) as against 12.4 million dinars
(17.4 million dollars) in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The index of the market has been loosing ground for the past 18
months, plunging from 180 points to around 145 points in recent
trading sessions, although the kingdom is emerging from a decade-
old economic recession and is expecting a three-percent economic
growth in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Foreign shares in the shareholding companies listed on the ASE
accounted for 43.3 percent of the market value of these firms, with
non-Jordanian Arab investors taking the lion's share of some 36.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of foreign ownership in the firms listed on the ASE is
in the banking sector, which accounted for 56.6 percent of the
total foreign ownership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
