<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Negotiator Rejects Israeli Accusations of Foot-Dragging in Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat on Wednesday refuted Israel's accusation that the
Palestinian side is foot-dragging in the Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has done everything possible to push the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks forward and the Israeli side can
not blame the Palestinians for the slow progress made in the final-
status talks, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian side is doing everything possible to reach a
peace agreement with Israel," Erekat told the Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, some Israeli officials, including Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, blamed the Palestinian side for foot-dragging
in the talks, saying Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is not ready
to make decisions on key issues that are being discussed in the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Such issues include the fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements,
Palestinian refugees, border and water.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have set September 13 as the deadline for reaching
a final peace agreement, and the Palestinian side is totally
committed to that, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of holding another three-way summit in the United
States between Arafat, Barak and U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Erekat said the time is not ripe for that summit, at least in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has told the Palestinians that preparations should be
done for such a summit and it is premature to say such a summit
will be held soon in the United States, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
