<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Become Next Chairman of NAM: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will become the next
chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) after South Africa,
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina told the parliament Tuesday, The
Bangladesh Observer reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The next summit of the NAM will be held in Dhaka in 2001, and
the tenure of the current chairman will end in the same year, the
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the chairmanship as a rare honor for the country,
Hasina said Bangladesh would be able to provide leadership to the
NAM for seven years as a member of the NAM troika, which consists
of the former, the current and the next chairman of the NAM.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 heads of state and government are expected to
attend the 13th NAM summit scheduled to be held in Dhaka in
September next year, and Hasina expressed the hope that all 114
member countries would attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
She said that a fund estimated at 4.21 billion taka (81 million
U.S. dollars) has been allocated for holding the summit which
includes construction of an international conference center and
guest houses for 5,000 delegates.
</P>
<P>
1.35 billion taka (26 million dollars) has been received as
grant and interest-free loan from the Chinese government for the
construction of the Bangabandhu International Conference Center,
the prime minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's House Rejects Results of Papua Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives(DPR) said here Wednesday that it rejected the
results of the "Papua National Congress".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after presiding over a
leadership meeting here, House Speaker Akbar Tandjung said, "the
DPR strongly refuses the results of the Papua National Congress
which have declared the province's independence."
</P>
<P>
It is the first official statement issued by the House
following the last week congress which was held in Jayapure,
capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we urge the government to take stern measures
through persuasive approaches to maintain the unitary state of
Indonesia," Tandjung added.
</P>
<P>
He asked the National Police (Polri) and the Indonesian
Military(TNI) "to show the seriousness in dealing with the Papua
issue and urge them to take anticipatory measures to prevent the
separatist movements in the province from spreading."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the possible interventions from external forces,
he said that, "we can not say that there were foreign government
involvements (in this case) because we don't have any evidences on
such a thing. But if we talk about non-govermental organization (
NGO), it is clear that some international and local NGO's were
involved in separatist movements in Irian Jaya (Papua)," Tandjung
said.
</P>
<P>
The one-week long "Papua National Congress" which was attended
by about 3000 representatives from 14 districts in the province,
declared on Sunday that the province would be no longer a part of
the unitary state of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid had warned
security forces in Papua not to resort to violence in an effort to
quash separatism in the province.
</P>
<P>
But Tandjung stressed that, "firstly the security forces should
take persuasive measures. But they need not to hesitate to crack
down separatist movements there, in case."
</P>
<P>
Papua is the largest island in Indonesia. It integrated into
Indonesia in 1969. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's oil Output Reaches 1.4 Millions bpd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's crude oil production in
April this year reached 1.4 million barrels per day (bpd), while
cumulative production during the fiscal year 1999/2000 reached 542.
9 millions barrels, a government official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a hearing with the House of Representatives (DPR)
Commission VIII for Mines and Energy, Director of the state-owned
oil company Pertamina Baihaki Hakim said that, "Indonesia's crude
oil production in April this year reached 1.406.203 bpd, while
cumulative production during the fiscal year 1999/2000 reached 542.
9 millions barrels (or 1.5 million bpd at average)."
</P>
<P>
The director said that Pertamina will keep increasing its crude
oil production for coming years.
</P>
<P>
"And to make the target successful we need 325 million U.S.
dollars for investments every year, we are still thinking how to
get the fund," Hakim added.
</P>
<P>
As a member of OPEC (Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries), Indonesia has been enjoying an oil price hike in
international market. The government set its oil price in the
current state budget at 18 U.S. dollars per barrels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
