<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Visits S.Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
arrives in Sierra Leone on Wednesday to review Britain's military
support for the government of the war-torn west African country.
</P>
<P>
Cook's visit follows Britain's announcement that its Royal
Marine Commando unit will pull out next week, leaving behind a
strengthened United Nations peacekeeping force and a 180-strong
British training team, reported the British Broadcasting
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
During his brief visit, Cook is expected to discuss how Britain
can continue to help its former colony during talks with President
Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
He will also seek guarantees that British-supplied weapons will
not go to child soldiers used by the Sierra Leone army.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Cook announced that Britain would seek a United
Nations resolution to ban trading in diamonds from rebel-held
areas of the war-torn African country.
</P>
<P>
He said diamonds had fuelled Sierra Leone's rebellion for the
past nine years while the country's people were among the world's
poorest, rebels could buy vast quantities of arms through the
trade of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that 11,000 international troops will be under
UN command from next week, with a further 5,000 expected to arrive
in Sierra Leone over coming months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
