<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Defends Petrol Price Hike Amid Nation Wide Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
Tuesday defended the government's decision to raise the petrol
price by 50 percent, saying the money freed from subsidization is
badly needed for alleviating the country's poor.
</P>
<P>
He told Adams Oshiomhole, leader of the country's umbrella
Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC) on Tuesday that the annual subsidy
for a low petrol price may amount to about 202 billion naira (2.
02 billion U. S. dollars) this year, reported Nigerian newspapers
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president said in African largest oil-exporting country's
capital Abuja that average Nigerians did not really benefit from
the subsidy, which if reduced he would guarantee a 25 percent
wage increase next year, and quicker steps in poverty alleviation
at all levels.
</P>
<P>
He promised that he would consider alleviating measures for the
hike and will not hesitate in continuing to dialogues with trade
unions, students and other interest groups on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Oshiomhole, who led a 23- man NLC delegation to the meeting, on
the other hand, expressed his "disappointment" with the
president.
</P>
<P>
He argued that Nigeria's economy is "generator- driven" due to
the inefficiency of the country's power plants. As a result, the
petrol price increase may lead to a situation where goods
produced in Nigeria would be costly while imported goods will be
cheaper, thus leading to retrenchment of workers.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's meeting was held when the country is shocked by
protests against the petrol hike in almost all major cities,
including the capital Abuja and economic hub Lagos.
</P>
<P>
In the capital, protesting workers Tuesday blocked the main
access road to the presidential villa and barred government
workers from entering their offices.
</P>
<P>
Most of the gas stations in Lagos remain shut on Wednesday and
car petrol peddlers seem to be having their good time on the
streets of the largest city in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
The nation wide "seat at home" strike, called up by the NLC
will take place from Thursday, if no breakthrough can be fostered
between the government and labor negotiators.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government last Thursday increased the country's
petrol price by 50 percent to 30 naira from 20 naira (100 naira
equals about one U. S. dollar) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The decision had met with mixed reactions in the country.
People in the business sector generally welcomed the move despite
the costs added to their operation, saying it is inevitable to
reduce the huge amount of money spent on subsidizing for a low
petrol price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
