<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya President Appeals for Aid to Combat Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moi told a press conference held at State House here that in
fact 80 percent of Kenyan population is current at risk,
appealing for local and International assistance to combat the
country's current drought distress.
</P>
<P>
He said due to circumstances which are beyond the government's
control, Kenya is in the grip of very worrying natural
calamities, which include extreme drought conditions, a spreading
and deepening famine and a devastating AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Over the past eight year, Kenya has witnessed vicissitudes of a
dry spell in 1992, heavy rains and floods in 1997 and 1998,
followed again by the current dry spell in most parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
So far the country has 30 districts affected by the current dry
spell and 18 of which have been severely hit, resulting in both
food and water insecurity for man and animal.
</P>
<P>
About two weeks ago, President Moi appealed for international
community to help the country's 23 million people likely to face
famine due to the long- spell drought following the dismal failure
of short rains last year and long rains this year.
</P>
<P>
"The government acknowledges that earlier appeals have resulted
in a high level of positive response. Given the intensity of the
calamity we wish to further appeal for more help," Moi said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the Kenyan government has been working in close
 consultation with the United Nations agencies.
</P>
<P>
He added, "the priority life saving requirements which my
government is appealing for, from the local and international
communities, have not been brought about by any conflict, civil
unrest or human displacements."
</P>
<P>
"Kenya is not at war with herself or with any other country.
The appeal for support is wholly due to natural calamities which
have befallen our beloved country," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The president estimated, "the cost of required commodities and
services will be in the region of 11.5 billion shillings (around
150 million U.S. dollars), of which food will take 85 percent,
while water and sanitation, health and nutrition, livestock,
agriculture and education will take the rest." 
</P>
</TEXT>
