<HEADLINE> Nobel Laureate on Five Trends Influencing World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Lawrence Klein, who was awarded a
Nobel Economics Prize in 1980, said here today that five trends
are currently having a huge impact on the development of the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
Klein, who came here to attend an international seminar on
development of western China, made the remark today while
delivering a lecture at Chongqing University, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The five trends include the advancement of technology and
telecommunications, the rapid development of products for civilian
use during the cold war, the high growth of economy with low
inflation, and the globalization of the economy. All of these
have made today's economy rather different from the past, said
Klein.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the change from industrial production
to service industry can not be called a "revolution," but only an
evolution.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that China's economy will have a new
development trend after joining the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Klein has become an honorary professor of the University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
