<HEADLINE> Scientists Provide Report on Development of Loess Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have recently
presented a report to the State Council on the sustainable
development of the Loess Plateau.
</P>
<P>
In the report, experts put forward some key measures including
building water cellars, reverting slope farmland to forests or
grasslands and adopting advanced technologies for agriculture and
animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Covering seven provinces or autonomous regions with an area of
360,000 square kilometers, the Loess Plateau has little rainfall,
and environment deterioration such as soil erosion has hindered
the overall development of the plateau.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that building water cellars to collect rainwater
is an effective way to ensure farmland harvests so long as some
water-saving irrigation technologies are adopted.
</P>
<P>
Since slope farmland merely accounts for 4.5 percent of total
arable land, reverting slope farmland to forests or grasslands
wouldn't seriously affect the grain production, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Experts suggested that livestock in the area should be fed in
stalls rather than grazing on the grassland. This will also help
improve water and soil conservation and stimulate the development
of the local feed processing industry.
</P>
<P>
Some experts from the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the
Chinese Academy of Engineering presented the report after in-depth
research on the Loess Plateau in the second half of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
