<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets With U.S. Secretary of State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
on Wednesday with visiting United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to discuss the latest developments in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Cairo earlier in the day during a regional
trip which has taken her to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule
areas.
</P>
<P>
She was expected to brief Mubarak on the outcome of her meetings
with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Israel on Monday in an attempt to help
Israel and the Palestinians meet a mid-September deadline for a
final peace deal. She announced after talks with Arafat in the West
Bank town of Ramallah on Tuesday that the Palestinians and Israel
will resume talks near Washington next week and that Arafat will
meet U.S. President Bill Clinton at the White House on June 14.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have set September 13 as the target
date for agreement on what they call final-status issues such as
the borders of a Palestinian state and the fate of Jerusalem,
Jewish settlements and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Before wrapping up the Mideast tour, Albright will also meet
with Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh, who is in the Egyptian
capital to attend Arab meetings, to discuss the possibility of
reviving the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, which broke off last
January.
</P>
<P>
But diplomats in Cairo are sceptical about the chance of
resuming the Syrian-Israeli talks, which were stalled due to
disputes between the two countries over Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan Heights and the control of water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
