<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman's LNG Co. is scheduled to export nearly 60
cargoes of clean fuel to South Korea's Korea Gas Corp (Kogas) next
year.
</P>
<P>
The volume of each export cargo will range between 63,000 and
68,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Central Bank of Oman has introduced a new
regulation aimed at limiting the amount of credit senior bankers
can extend to companies they control.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the move is aimed to prevent top bankers from
extending unjustifiable loans to finance their businesses.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the central bank reinstated a 13-percent interest
rate ceiling on personal loans after saying bankers "were taking
advantage of small borrowers" by charging them interest of up to 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. computer giant Sun Microsystems, the Peres
Center for Peace, the Palestinian National Authority, and five
Israeli and Palestinian universities on Tuesday signed an
unprecedented agreement to establish and upgrade computer
facilities for Palestinian and Israeli universities and promote
cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to promote dialogues between the Israeli and
Palestinian universities. The Israeli universities will help
academics at the Palestinian university to design curricula, set up
a computer security system and gain access to new technologies.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- About 24 percent of female entrepreneurs in start-
up companies in Israel are aged 55 or above, according to a survey
published by the Israel Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
Ronit Silon, chairwoman of the Female CEO Forum at the
association, said that the findings showed that 60 percent of
female entrepreneurs have doctorate degrees while only 8 percent do
not hold an academic degree.
</P>
<P>
Female entrepreneurs are mainly located in software development
companies and biotechnology, while there is a relatively low female
presence in managerial positions in companies in the fields of
telecommunications, information technology and wireless
communications.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- El Al Israel Airlines loses 55 million dollars a
year because it does not fly on Shabbat and holidays, according to
a study by Israeli account Yitzhak Swary, which was submitted to
the Ne'eman Committee preparing for the airline's privatization.
</P>
<P>
The committee will be meeting on Wednesday to discuss the
question of El Al's Shabbat and holiday losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
