<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Exchange Reserve Stands at 26.77 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign exchange
reserve at the end of May stood at 26.77 billion U.S. dollars, or
40 million dollars more than that of the previous week, a press
release issued by the central bank, Bank Indonesia, said.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to receipts from the export of oil and
other commodities, the press release was quoted by the Antara News
Agency Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The release said the figure 26.77 billion dollars was computed
on current rate according to the concept of the International
Reserve and Foreign Currency Liquidity, which makes part of the
financial data publication based on the Special Data Dissemination
Standard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's net foreign exchange reserve was
registered at 16.01 billion dollars. It was computed according to
the foreign exchange reserves on constant rate, minus the gross
foreign obligation, plus the net forward position, and then minus
the minimum obligatory giro of foreign exchanges of commercial
banks at Bank Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The figure, according to the central bank, is compatible with
the computation in the Letter of Intent agreed upon by the
Indonesian government and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
