<HEADLINE> Malaysian Police to Cooperate with ACA to Fight Against Graft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Malaysia Police and
the Anti Corruption Agency (ACA) Wednesday agreed to set up a
joint graft prevention committee under a memorandum of
understanding (MOU) signed here.
</P>
<P>
The MOU was signed by Police Director of Management Mohamed
Bakri Omar and ACA Deputy Director General (operations) Ahmad Said
Hamdan and witnessed by Inspector General of Police Norian Mai and
ACA Director General Ahmad Zaki Husin.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Zaki said on the occasion that the cooperation with the
police in the fight against graft will focus more on integrated
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
To a question on whether graft in the police force has reached
an alarming level for such cooperation to be instituted, he said
the problem was still under control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police chief said the setting up of the joint
committee is not a move to protect officers and members of the
police force, and will not affect ACA investigations against
members of the police force nor investigations by the police
against its own members.
</P>
<P>
Norian said all parties, including the public, must play their
part in the fight against graft so that the fight would be
successful.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on March 28, the ACA entered into cooperation with the
Road Transport Department in the fight against graft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
