<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzania Unveils Tough Code for Upcoming Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhang Dacheng
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian National Electoral
Commission (NEC) has issued a draft code of conduct for the
October general elections, barring government and ruling party
leaders from using their power for political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The NEC Chairman Judge Lewis Makame told a meeting with leaders
of political parties here on Tuesday that the draft intended to
level the playing ground for the second multiparty elections
scheduled for October 29.
</P>
<P>
According to a timetable issued by the NEC early this year, the
 registration of voters will be conducted between August 1 and 21
while nomination of candidates will be made on August 13, and
election campaigns between August 14 and October 28.
</P>
<P>
Makame said during the campaign period, the government and
ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) leaders are not allowed to use
state planes, vehicles, offices and government rest houses during
campaigning tours.
</P>
<P>
The draft said the government should ensure that state organs
provide security to all political parties during campaigning
rallies, demonstrations and elections.
</P>
<P>
The government is also required to ensure its state media
organs provide equal opportunity to all political parties and
assist the media in providing the public with correct and balanced
information.
</P>
<P>
The code also warned the political parties as well as religious
leaders against using churches and mosques for campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The code prohibits the carrying of any kind of weapon in
political rallies, meetings, demonstrations and no party is
allowed to conduct meetings or demonstrations in areas close to
where another party is holding its meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, CCM will convene a special congress at its
headquarters in central town of Dodoma later this week to chose
its presidential candidates for both the Union and Zanzibar
governments.
</P>
<P>
Following a two-day session of CCM Central Committee (CC) in
Dar es Salaam Tuesday, the CCM Secretary General Phillip Mangula
said that all four Zanzibar presidential candidates will be
forwarded to the National Executive Committee (NEC) of the ruling
party which begins its two-day meeting in Dodoma tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The four candidates who have successfully sailed through the
crucial CC scrutiny are Zanzibar Chief Minister Mohammed Gharib
Bilal, Zanzibar Minister for Communications and Transport Amani
Abeid Karume, Zanzibar Minister for Finance Amina Salum Ali and
the Union Deputy Minister for Finance Abdisalaam Issa Khatib.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day session, the CC also discussed President
Benjamin Mkapa's eligibility and qualifications as the sole
candidate for the Union Presidency which he won in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the opposition Civic United Front (CUF)
is meeting in western town of Mwanza Wednesday to endorse its
candidates for the Union and Zanzibar presidencies.
</P>
<P>
CUF is expected to endorse its chairman Ibrahim Lipumba as the
sole candidate to run for Union presidency and the party's
Secretary General Seif Shariff Hamad for the Zanzibar presidency.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say Hamad who gave CCM a headache in the last general
elections is still the strongest opposition presidential candidate
in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had a single political party, the CCM, from 1965 until
1992 when the multiparty system was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The October elections will be the second multiparty elections
since 1995, but the first time in the country's post-independence
history for presidential, parliamentary and civic elections to be
held simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
All the 13 fully registered political parties run for the
elections which are likely to be dominated by the ruling CCM, at
least on the mainland as President Mkapa is expected to win a
second five-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Awareness of Family Planning Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More and more Ethiopians,
particularly young people, have become aware of the importance of
family planning, a signed article on the Ethiopian Herald
newspaper said Wednesday
</P>
<P>
Population issues have become a common topic at hospitals,
schools, work places, factories, market place, and even churches
and mosques in Ethiopia,which has a total population of about 60
million, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Application of family planning, which was only four percent in
1993, has now reached 10 percent, the article said, noting the
percentage is expected to grow to 44 percent by 2015.
</P>
<P>
Today's increased demand for family planning methods is not the
result only of availability of services, but also a growing
number of young women wishing to prevent unwanted pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia officially launched its National Population Policy in
1993, two years after Mengistu Haile-Mariam's rule was overthrown
by the ruling Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front.
</P>
<P>
Due to wrong premises and ideology of pre-1991 period, the
article said,
</P>
<P>
population issues and the consequence of rapid growth were given
little attention. No commitments were made to consider population
issues.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of population policy in the country,
population offices have been established in all states with most
of them doing remarkable jobs.
</P>
<P>
During the past few years, the non-governmental organizations
and mass media in the country have also played important part to
promote the implementation of family planning policy.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the problems in practice of family planning, the
article said that financial constraints and the shortage of
trained personnel are major obstacles to efficiently run the
government-sponsored programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
