<HEADLINE> UNIFIL Reinforcement Unnecessary: French FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said Tuesday evening that a reinforcement of the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) is less necessary since
tension is easing on the Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
"As for what concerns the reinforcement of the UNIFIL, the
situation now is not the same as a few days ago. It seems that
there is less need to increase the UNIFIL," Vedrine said during a
yearly reception of high school and college students at the
foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
France is hesitating to join an expanded U.N. peacekeeping
operation, because Lebanon has not sent government troops to its
border area with Israel to take over control of the area from
Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
But the Lebanese government said Wednesday that it will fully
cooperate with the United Nations in implementing U.N. resolution
425, if the United Nations verifies that Israel has pulled out
from Lebanon's southern border area in conformity to the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan has suggested the increase of
the peacekeepers in Lebanon from 4,500 soldiers at present to 7,
900.
</P>
<P>
France now has 249 soldiers serving in the UNIFIL, which was
deployed in the Middle East state in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
