<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Child labor Convention Ratified by 27 Governments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Up to 27 governments have ratified
an ILO convention on the abolition of the worst forms of child
labor since it was adopted in June 1999, according to the
International Labor Organization (ILO) here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the child labor convention has achieved the fastest
ratification pace in the ILO history, ILO Director-General Juan
Somavia applauded the willingness of so many ILO member states to
expedite ratification. He reiterated his intention to make the
abolition of the worst forms of child labor "a global cause".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to delegates from the ratifying countries at the
International Labor Conference, Somavia said that "this rapid pace
of ratification is evidence of the growing support for global
action against child labor, particularly its worst forms and gives
us hope that the elimination of this scourge will become a reality
for millions of children who face exploitation today."
</P>
<P>
The convention requires countries to ban the worst forms of
child labor including those which have a debilitating effect on
the health, moral or psychological well-being of children and
which are likely to severely impede a child's normal growth into
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
Those activities include work in dangerous industrial
activities such as mining, or illegal activities such as
prostitution and drug trafficking, work under extreme conditions
of heat or cold, or work that involves exposure to chemicals or
other hazardous substances.
</P>
<P>
The ILO expects the child labor convention, which will come
into force on November 19, 2000, to get ratification from as many
as 12 new countries before the end of the current session of the
International Labor Conference on June 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
