<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Killed, 81 Others Injured in Cerkes Quake: Turkish Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Two people were killed and 81 others
wounded in a 5.9-magnitude quake which occurred on Tuesday morning
in the northern Turkish province of Cankiri, the Prime Ministry
Crisis Management Centre announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Buildings in the rural areas of Cerkes and Orta towns, the
epicenter of the quake, were heavily damaged while 70 percent of
the buildings in Cankiri city, 100 kilometers northeast of Turkey's
capital Ankara, were slightly damaged except five buildings
demolished, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said 86 buildings were damaged in Cerkes, 55
collapsed and 300 seriously damaged in Orta while Cankiri Governor
Halil Ulusoy said a total of 4,594 buildings were damaged in the
province.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has sent 25 personnel and 1000 tents to
Orta town while another 2000 tents will be added, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the residents in Orta town spent the night
outdoors as they were afraid of another quake in the region where
both tents and drinking water are needed.
</P>
<P>
It also said the Ankara Governorship sent 250 packages of food,
100 tents and three damage assessment teams to Cubuk town of Ankara
province, which was shaken strongly.
</P>
<P>
Red Crescent, Turkish humanitarian relief agency, sent 416
tents, 1,010 blankets, nine mobile kitchens, 4,158 kilos of food
product, one mobile clinic, five generators, three ambulances and
three health teams to the areas which suffered damage in the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
Red Crescent authorities said they will continue to send more
aid to the region as they find out about the people's needs.
</P>
<P>
"There is no damage in Cankiri railway and Ankara's Esenboga
airport. A mobile satellite telephone line was set up between the
Crisis Centre and Orte town. No damage was reported in electric
networks," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a quake-prone country which suffered a loss of 20,000
lives in the two devastating earthquakes last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Set to Form New, Narrow Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (XInhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
is trying to set up a narrow coalition as a pre-emptive measure in
the face of a vote on three bills designed to dissolve the 15th
Knesset (parliament), Barak's office announced Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Barak had to take measures as three of his six-party coalition
have voiced support for the bills which are to be voted in the
Knesset as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The defective coalition parties include the ultra-Orthodox Shas
party which holds 17 seats in the parliament, the five-seat holder
National Religious Party and the Yisrael Ba'aliya headed by
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
Shinui, a religious reform party which has six seats in the
Knesset, and Am Ehad, or One Nation party, are potential new
partners for the narrow-based coalition.
</P>
<P>
Though the two parties have indicated support for the bills,
they might change their stance if their respective demands are met.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset was originally scheduled only to vote on the early-
elections bill tabled by Knesset member Avigdor Lieberman on
Wednesday. Seeing that Lieberman appeared to have secured a
majority for the vote, the opposition Likud Knesset members Silvan
Shalom and Limor Livnat, who had proposed identical bills, decided
to put them to a vote on Wednesday too.
</P>
<P>
Barak broke off negotiations with Shas party Monday night after
Shas threatened to support the Lieberman bill. Shas has been
demanding millions of additional dollars for its bankrupt, poorly-
managed religious school system.
</P>
<P>
Barak said his government will not give in to threats, whether
external or internal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
