<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT Israeli Parliament Backs Early Election in Preliminary Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset (parliament)
Wednesday passed in a preliminary reading a motion proposed by
opposition parties to hold early elections, an event that may
hamper Prime Minister Ehud Barak's efforts to push forward the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The motion, submitted by Knesset member Avigdor Lieberman from
National Union, Yisrael Beiteinu and Silvan Shalom from the major
opposition Likud party, was approved with a vote of 58-47, with 15
Knesset members not attending the vote.
</P>
<P>
The bill only needs a simple majority in the 120-seat Knesset in
Wednesday's preliminary reading voting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
