<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Police Detain 10,000 Illegal Foreign Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian police have detained some
10,000 illegal foreign workers since the start of this year in a
nationwide campaign to streamline the labor market, police said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the number of foreign workers questioned by police was
believed to be merely the tip of an iceberg given the size of the
illegal foreign labor force. Some 1 to 1.5 million foreigners are
working without permits in Jordan, most of them are Egyptians,
Iraqis and other Arab nationals.
</P>
<P>
Only 25,000 of the foreign labor force have obtained valid
working permits from the labor ministry, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The illegal workers were given a week to rectify their legal
status or face deportation, an official with the interior ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the illegal workers live in the capital city Amman,
Zarqa, Irbid and the Jordan Valley, the most populous areas of the
desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Successive governments in the kingdom, for fear of offending
Arab countries, have been reluctant to curb the inflow of illegal
foreign workers and implement the labor law which allows for
foreign labors in only four sectors, namely agriculture,
construction, domestic work and sanitation.
</P>
<P>
The interior and labor ministries launched a nationwide campaign
from the second half of 1999 to check out illegal foreign workers
as part of the government's efforts to streamline the labor market
and to create more jobs for Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
However, Jordanians have shunned low-income jobs currently done
by illegal foreign workers, though the unemployment rate in the
kingdom stands at 14 to 15 percent by official statistics, if not
the 27 percent by independent estimates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, DPRK Resume Talks in Malaysia on Missing Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) resumed talks here
Wednesday on finding American soldiers missing in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
"The primary goal of these talks is to renew bilateral
discussions with the Korean People's Army to achieve the fullest
possible accounting of American servicemen," a statement issued by
the U.S. Embassy said.
</P>
<P>
The American team from the U.S. Defense Department would seek
to reach agreement on the conduct of a single, expanded joint
recovery operation in areas where North Korea claimed to have
disinterred four or five sets of U.S. remains, it said.
</P>
<P>
The United States hopes that the talks will lead to the fullest
possible accounting of American soldiers missing in action during
the Korean War, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The US-North Korea talks here are slated to go on until June 10.
</P>
