<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Halts Troop Withdrawal From Kisangani, Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda People's Defence Forces
(UPDF) has halted its withdrawal from Kisangani, a northeast city
of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), due to the
skirmishes with the Rwandan Patriotic Army (RPA).
</P>
<P>
"The UPDF has stoped its troop withdrawal from Kisangani,"
Ugandan Army Spokesman Phinehas Katirima told Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan armies clashed after a UPDF's vehicle was
attacked and destroyed in Kisangani Monday morning. The UPDF had
repulsed RPA forces which by Tuesday night attacked 18 UPDF
positions in Kisangani, according to army sources.
</P>
<P>
Uganda was committed to the troop withdrawal plan, but would
not go ahead without an immediate cease-fire, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the withdrawal plan, Kisangani was zoned and the
demilitarization was to be phased, said a press statement signed
by James Wapakabulo, chairman of the committee on the region.
</P>
<P>
"The first phase involved the demilitarization of zone one
which is Bangoka Airport, La Forestiere and Lubutu junction areas
supposed to take five days, and then zone two, which was due to
have started on Monday, included the pull-out from the town, Simi
Simi Airport and Kapalata," said Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
He accused the RPA of withdrawing only 20 miles (about 32
kilometers) from the Kisangani center instead of 100 miles (160
kilometers).
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda have their troops stationed in Kisangani
where they have supported rival rebel factions fighting against
the DRC President Laurent Kabila. The skirmishes on Monday and
Tuesday between the two armies are the latest following the
clashes early last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
