<HEADLINE> China's Environmental Protection Project Shown At Hanover Expo 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive environment
protection project in east China's Jiangxi Province has been shown
at the Expo 2000, which started on June 1 in Germany's Hanover.
</P>
<P>
The project commenced in 1983 and covers nearly 120,000 sq km,
including mountainous areas, the valley of the local Ganjiang
River and the areas of the Poyang Lake, China's largest freshwater
lake.
</P>
<P>
Project organizers are also invited to attend an international
seminar, "the world is a garden", according to Wu Guochen,
director of the committee of the project.
</P>
<P>
The project will help curb environmental deterioration,
flooding and drought in Poyang Lake areas and Ganjiang River
valley, as well as help impoverished peasants to develop
ecological resources.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi Province has cooperated with more than 20 international
organizations and countries to protect the local environment.
Forest coverage rate in Jiangxi Province has increased from 31
percent to 54 percent. Meanwhile, more than four million local
people are no longer on the brink of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The project has been listed among the first group of projects
on China's "Agenda 21". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
