<HEADLINE> New Zealand Frigate Heads for Solomons as Violence Flares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A New Zealand Navy frigate is en
route to Solomon Islands as reports came in of heavy fighting on
the eastern outskirts of the capital Honiara Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Television NZ reported the fighting was apparently in the area
where the territories of the Guerrilla Isatabu Freedom Movement
and the leaders of this week's attempted coup, the Malaita Eagle
Force,meet.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Minister of Foreign Affairs and Trade Phil Goff was
quoted as saying that racial tensions within the Solomons remain
dangerously high and that violence could erupt into civil war.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand is sending the frigate Te Mana to Solomon Islands
as a precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
A navy spokesperson, Lieutenant Commander Bill Morley, said Te
Mana is expected to arrive there sometime on Saturday, but will
remain in international waters pending a further decision.
</P>
<P>
He said the frigate is going in case any of New Zealand's 225
nationals need to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Television NZ also reported that New Zealand Minister Goff, who
is now in London attending a meeting of the Commonwealth
Ministerial Action Group, will join his Australian, Malaysian and
Malawi counterparts in Sydney on Friday and travel to Honiara, and
then to Suva in Fiji to increase the pressure for a full return to
democracy there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
