<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Bills Approved by Philippine Legislators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine House of
Representatives has approved on third reading bills on e-commerce,
investment and the election in the Autonomous Region in Muslim
Mindanao (ARMM), a senior legislator said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The three bills -- the E-Commerce bill, the resetting of ARMM
election next year and the amendment to the Omnibus Investment
Code of 1997 -- "were finally passed by the House members after a
lengthy and thorough consideration," said House Majority
Floorleader Eduardo Gullas.
</P>
<P>
According to Gullas, the E-Commerce bill provides for a legal
framework to facilitate domestic and international exchange of
information, dealings, transactions, arrangements and contracts
through the utilization of network.
</P>
<P>
Gullas said the approved measure would also penalize any person
who shall hack, alter, forge, inflict damages, violate secrecy,
misuse, or other illegal use of electronic documents sent,
received, stored or complied.
</P>
<P>
The amendment to Omnbus Investment Code would make the
Philippines mere competitive with its neighbors to attracting
foreign investments, Gullas said, adding the amendments will give
the country's fighting chance to attract foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Gullas also said the resetting of the ARMM elections -- the
third time since 1998, the elections of the ARMM -- would be moved
from September this year to May 2001, coinciding with the next
simultaneous senatorial and local elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
