<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Officers Sacked for Bribe-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Four Kenyan police officers have
been dismissed from the force for bribe-taking and abuse of office
on the orders of Police Commander Philemon Abong'o, local
newspapers said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two police officers sacked, a chief inspector and a
constable attached to the Kaloleni Police Station in Coast
Province in eastern Kenya, were filmed by journalists as they
collected the bribes at a roadblock from motorists over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Two others, the former Likoni Police Station chief and his
constable, were sacked for stealing police exhibits from Coast
provincial police headquarters worth 300,000 shillings (around
4,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The disciplinary action were revealed Tuesday by Coast Province
police chief Stanley Manyinya.
</P>
<P>
The police chief announced that his force has started to crack
down on corruption and that anybody found practising the vice
would face the full force of the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
