<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0740 GMT, June 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA -- Apart from an increase in thyroid cancer, there is no
evidence of a major health problem attributable to radiation
exposure as a result of the Chernobyl incident, said a report
approved by the United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects
of Atomic Radiation (UNSCEAR) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There have been about 1,800 cases of thyroid cancer found in
children who were exposed at the time of the accident, and there
may be more such cases during the next decades, said UNSCEAR in
its 2000 report to the General Assembly. Apart from this increase,
there is no additional scientific evidence of a major public
health problem due to radiation from the nuclear accident, it
noted. (Vienna-UNSCEAR-Chernobyl)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Yugoslavian government Tuesday made a strong
protest regarding the United Nations' mission in Kosovo and the
international peacekeeping force KFOR for wounding Serbian
residents.
</P>
<P>
British troops in the KFOR shot and injured four Serbs,
including a child, in the village of Gracanica Tuesday, said
Stanimir Vukicevic, chairman of the Yugoslav committee cooperating
with the U.N. mission in Kosovo (UNMIK). Albanian extremists also
wounded five Serbs in the village the same day, with British
troops on the scene, Vukicevic said in a protest letter sent to
the U.N. mission. (Yugoslavia-KFOR-Protest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Bosnia launched unified national border police on
Tuesday when 85 Muslim, Croat and Serb officers began functioning
at the Sarajevo international airport, the Oslobodjenje newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
The national border service will be made up of 3,000 members,
responsible for the security of the country's 1,665-kilometer
border line. The newspaper quoted U.N. special envoy to Bosnia
Paul Klein as saying that the national border service is crucial
for fighting against trafficking and corruption. (Croate-Bosnia-
Border Police)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albania and Bulgaria signed a protocol Tuesday
agreeing to promote bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed at the end of a two-day meeting held by
the mixed committee of economic, industrial and technological
cooperation between the two countries, insists that bilateral
cooperation in economic and trade areas should be further
strengthened in accordance with the Stability Pact reached by
southeastern European countries. Albania and Bulgaria have seen an
exchange of visits by their presidents and high level officials
since last year, but economic and trade cooperation between the
two Balkan countries remains at a relatively low level. (Albania-
Bulgaria-Cooperation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
