<HEADLINE> Athens to Be Focused on Task for 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CANBERRA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Athens Mayor Dimitris
Avramopoulos said Wednesday the city is focused on the task ahead
for the 2004 Olympic preparation, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
In April, Juan Antonio Samaranch was highly critical of 2004
host city Athens, saying he had never seen a Games with so many
organizational problems as Athens in his 20 years as International
Olympic Committee (IOC) president.
</P>
<P>
But in Sydney on Wednesday en route to Uluru in central
Australia for Thursday's start of the Olympic torch relay,
Avramopoulos said Athens was back on track.
</P>
<P>
"When Mr. Samaranch came out (to Athens) and made those
comments I went to visit him in Lausanne," Avramopoulos told a
gathering of mainly Greek-language journalists. "We had a long,
sincere and cordial talk."
</P>
<P>
Avramopoulos, a member of the Athens 2004 organizing committee
(ATHOC), said since the comments were made, Athens had taken swift
action.
</P>
<P>
"We all gathered and we talked about it, we accepted that
certain things had not been done and there was some very important
political decisions made," Avramopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
"The first change to the organization of ATHOC assures that we
are on a good and positive track and things will go very very well
in the future."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis'
appointment of 44-year-old lawyer Gianna Angelopoulos to the
position of ATHOC president. Angelopoulos was the architect behind
Athens' successful 2004 bid.
</P>
<P>
Avramopoulos, 47, said the Olympics would be a unique
opportunity to improve one of Athens' biggest negatives _ its
appearance.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very optimistic and believe that by the end of 2003
Athens will be among the best cities in Europe," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
