<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South America To Back South Africa for Cup Host </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- South America is set to support
South Africa's bid to host the 2006 soccer World Cup, a British
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of a pact in which African countries would
back a Brazilian bid to host the World Cup in 2010, said the
Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which is due to be finalised next week,
Brazil would ensure South Africa gained the votes of the three
South American members of FIFA's 24-man executive committee, which
meets to choose the 2006 host country next month.
</P>
<P>
 Brazil is competing with England, Germany, South Africa and
Morocco for the right to hold the event. But the Financial Times
said the South American country might consider withdrawing its
candidacy as part of the agreement with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The deal was brokered by South Africa's campaign director
Danny Jordaan, the head of the Brazilian football federation
Ricardo Teixeira and former FIFA president Joao Havelange,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Teixeira is one of the three South American members of the
executive committee. Argentina's Julio Grondona and Paraguay's
Nicolas Leoz are the others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
