<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Fossils of Dinosaur Found in Yuanmou Man's Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 7 (Xinhua)-- Archaeologists recently excavated
two more complete sets of dinosaur skeletons in the county of
Yuanmou, the "home of Yuanmou Man, in the Yi Autonomous Prefecture
of Chuxiong, in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The excavation began in late April after a villager in the
county discovered a fossil in last November which was later
confirmed as a fossilized dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
Experts believed that the finding is another major
archaeological discovery following the find of the first Yuanmou
Man in 1965 at Shangnabang Village in Yuanmou County.
</P>
<P>
Yuanmou Man which dates back to around 1.7 million years ago is
the earliest homo sapien found in China.
</P>
<P>
The latest three fossils which belong to the Cretaceous Period
(some 135 million and 60 million years ago) may help explain
possible reasons for the extinction of dinosaurs and the origin of
human and the relationships between dinosaur and human beings.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is abundant in various pithecanthropus fossils. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Pasturing Area Emerging in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- When people talk about pastures,
they often refer to the grasslands in such areas as Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region. But this time, they mean Guangdong province in
south China.
</P>
<P>
Adjacent to Hong Kong and Macao, Guangdong enjoys a good
consumer market. Since 1980s, the province has opened its animal
husbandry and livestock market.
</P>
<P>
So far, the province has attracted 1.2 billion U.S. dollars of
investment in the fields of animal raising and related products
processing.
</P>
<P>
In order to adapt to the development of market economy,
Guangdong has focused on developing grain-saving and fast-growing
varieties of poultry.
</P>
<P>
The total number of poultry raised in the province rose to more
than one billion in 1999, compared with some 100 million in 1980,
accounting for nearly a quarter of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The province also plans to feed more vegetarian and muscle
livestock in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
To meet domestic demand, Guangdong has begun to export
livestock products such as chicken and pig to Hong Kong, Macao and
overseas market.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province reported a total animal husbandry
output worth 21.9 billion yuan, with exports amounting to one
billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
