<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Fund for Improving Lake, River Water Quality in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province have
been carrying out a program under which World Bank loans are used
to improve the quality of water in six local lakes and rivers.
</P>
<P>
Hubei, dubbed as a "province with 1,000 lakes", abounds in
water resources. But the quality of water in most lakes and
rivers has been worsening as a result of random discharge of
sewage and industrial waste water.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang Jiazhi, head of Hubei provincial
environmental protection bureau, the program, initiated in early
1998, has pooled a total investment of 1.9 billion yuan (about 229
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Beneficiaries are Donghu, Moshui lakes in Wuhan, the provincial
capital, and Cihu Lake in Huangshi, another industrial city in
eastern Hubei, and Xiaoqing, Zhupi and Fuhe rivers in the province.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, a great number of sewage treatment plants
and works to hold up and treat industrial waste water have been
built so that sewage and industrial waste water will be discharged
into lakes and rivers only after treatment.
</P>
<P>
Some 884 million yuan ( about 107 million U.S. dollars) has so
far been spent in constructing various waste water treatment works,
including the use of 40 million U.S. dollars loans from World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Facilities to hold up sewage and industrial waste water for the
three lakes will be completed at the end of this year and by then,
the water quality in the three lakes will turn for the better,
said Yang, adding that pollution harnessing works for the three
rivers are expected to be finished in 2004.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Hubei Province has implemented regulations on
preventing and harnessing water pollution in the valley of the
province's Hanjiang River, a major tributary of the mighty Yangtze
River, as of May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
