<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Reaches 117 in Earthquake in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Most of the dead and injured have come from the provincial
capital of Bengkulu, about 536 kilometers northwest of Jakarta,
and surrounding districts.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they had yet to assess the full impact of the
earthquake because of cut communications with outlying areas of
the province.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, Sunday's earthquake,
measuring 7.9 on the Richter Scale, has damaged thousands of
houses in the province, with financial losses estimated at 30
billion rupiah (about 3.8 million U.S. dollars). In South Bengkulu,
the quake has reportedly damaged an irrigation system worth 7.5
billion rupiah and roads worth 4.5 billion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
But relief efforts have been hampered by the closure of the
provincial airport and bad weather, with supplies of food,
medicine and plastic sheeting only trickling in.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals in Bengkulu city have been struggling with a shortage
of beds, medicine and blood. They have resorted to treating
victims in hospital parking lots.
</P>
<P>
An information officer with the International Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent Societies Jessica Barry was quoted as
saying that a team of experts would arrive in Bengkulu on
Wednesday to assess damage and deliver medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
Many Bengkulu residents spent Tuesday in makeshift tents, as
minor tremors played havoc with jittery nerves. Seismologists said
more than 500 light tremors have been recorded since the temblor
hit. The aftershocks were going down in magnitude but they would
continue through the week and expected to vanish only in two or
three weeks' time.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has appealed for help from around the
world, and the international community has been quick to respond.
Australia, the United States, Japan, Singapore and Thailand have
pledged emergency aid to help survivors of the quake in Bengkulu,
home to 1.4 million people.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's far-flung islands are regularly hit by earthquakes.
At least 45 people died last month when an earthquake measuring 6.
5 on the Richter Scale hit Central Sulawesi and some neighboring
islands.
</P>
<P>
The worst quake to hit Indonesia in the past decade was in
1992, when 2,200 people died in a string of eastern islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
