<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel delays release of Timna processor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp., the world's
largest semiconductor maker, said it has delayed by several months
the launch of its integrated processor, code-named Timna, because
it needs to develop a new method to connect the integrated
processor to standard memory.
</P>
<P>
The delay, from the second half of this year until the first
quarter of 2001, is related to problems with a component known as
a memory translation hub (MTH) that allows Intel processors
designed for specialized Rambus memory to use traditional
synchronous memory instead, according to reports from the chip
giant Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Intel recalled nearly one million motherboards that
used an MTH and Intel's 820 chipset because signal problems with
the MTH could cause systems to crash and potentially lead to data
loss.
</P>
<P>
The Timna processor is Intel's first so-called integrated chip
that combines the central processor unit core, memory controller
and a graphics controller. It was developed for personal computer
systems that cost 800 dollars and below.
</P>
<P>
Timna will be pitched as a lower-cost product than the Celeron
chip, the Pentium-class processor aimed at low-cost PCs. Intel
will announce by the end of the month Celeron chips that run at
700 megahertz, up from 600 megahertz currently.
</P>
<P>
Analyst Peter Glaskowsky of MicroDesign Resources said the woes
with the MTH appear to reflect deep flaws in the physical design
of that component. Reworking the physical design of a chip
typically takes four or five months, he said, adding that Intel
may have already begun that process.
</P>
<P>
The delay also could put additional pricing pressure on Intel.
The chips needed for, say, a 600-MHz Timna-based computer were
expected to cost 7 to 10 dollars less than if PC makers used a 600-
MHz Celeron with a chipset containing integrated graphics. Such a
discount could reduce the retail price of PCs by 30 dollars, noted
one analyst.
</P>
<P>
Intel has been struggling to keep up with strong demand for
Celeron and Pentium III processors since last year's holiday
season. Other analysts believe that the Timna delay could free up
enough capacity to help Intel avoid a similar crunch this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Ka-shing Honored With Entrepreneur Award in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Li Ka-shing, chairman of
the Cheung Kong Group of Companies, was made the first Chinese
here Tuesday to receive the International Distinguished
Entrepreneur Award (IDEA).
</P>
<P>
At a gala dinner of about 900 guests, John Fraser, chairman of
the Nominating Committee for the IDEA Associates, praised Li's
success as one of the world's outstanding entrepreneur.
</P>
