<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Reiterates Cautious Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp., the world's
largest software maker that has been battling a government
antitrust suit, reiterated its outlook on Tuesday for lowered
revenue growth despite seeing stronger PC demand, according to
reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
Chief Financial Officer John Connors said the company sees
industry-wide personal computer sales growing 12 to 15 percent for
its fiscal year beginning July.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft, which has a wide view of the computer industry
because it sells operating systems for most personal computers,
cited slow PC growth as one reason it had lowered its outlook in
April for year-to-year revenue growth to 15 percent from 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
Connors reiterated Tuesday that 20 percent revenue growth rates
were not within reach, despite a recovery in the business PC
market and the release of the Windows 2000 operating system, which
he said was on track.
</P>
<P>
Another reason behind the cautious outlook, according to
Connors, is because the twists and turns of the government's
antitrust lawsuit against the Redmond, Wash.-based company had
taken its toll on the spirits of employees.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it would be accurate or honest to say that a
lawsuit like this -- and the continuous negative stories -- does
not have an effect on morale," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he predicted that in fiscal year 2001 the company
expects to achieve 15 percent year-over-year revenue growth rates,
which he called "a lot of dough."
</P>
<P>
"Once we get the legal volume turned down and the DOJ (
Department of Justice) case goes into the appeals process, I think
we can have the kind of growth we feel good about and the people
in this room can feel good about," he told investors at the
conference.
</P>
<P>
He said Microsoft had not yet begun to map out how a breakup
would be carried out, though a ruling in the antitrust suit, which
could force a break-up of the company, is expected as early as
this week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
