<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Honors War Heroes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The people are required to observe two minutes silence at 9:30
a.m.local time (0330 GMT) as tribute to the fallen war heroes.
Traffic also came to a standstill at this time as a mark of
respect to them.
</P>
<P>
A national ceremony to mark the day was held here under the
patronage of President Chandrika Kumaratunga at the Presidential
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
It began with a bevy of school girls reciting a special song
dedicated to the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Later the national flag was drawn full mast and the president
accepted donations to the National Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 17-year-old civil war between
the government and Tamil Tiger rebels who are fighting for a
separate state for minority Tamils.
</P>
<P>
The war has escalated as the rebels were engaged in a ferocious
assault in a bid to retake their former stronghold of the northern
Jaffna peninsula since overrunning a strategic base in April.
</P>
<P>
The government has vowed to defend Jaffna and taken various
steps to boost the morale of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
While government institutions were issued directions how
ceremonies should be conducted at their workplaces, most private
establishments and individuals joined hands to make the
countrywide program a success.
</P>
<P>
The government's Independent Television Network and Lak Handa
radio jointly organized a motorcade from Nugegoda to Panadura,
south of Colombo, to collect funds for the National Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
A commemoration ceremony organized by Airport and Aviation
Services was held a the Ratmalana Airport. Similar ceremonies were
conducted at several towns in the provinces sponsored by various
organizations.
</P>
<P>
In a message to mark the occasion, President Kumaratunga called
on the people to join the government in saluting the members of
the Sri Lanka armed services and police who are dead, missing in
action,disabled and those who are fighting a valiant battle to
keep the nation together.
</P>
<P>
She asked the people to assist the families of the soldiers by
conducting religious observances and blessing on the forces and
their relatives and ensure them that society has not forgotten
them.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga said, "our cherished dream of peace can be achieved
only through a political solution of giving space for every
citizen of this country to live in dignity and harmony."
</P>
<P>
She said to achieve this end a consensus is being reached by
all political parties to forge ahead with a new constitution which
will spell out a new vision for nationhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
