<HEADLINE> U.S. CIA Involved in Montegegrin Official's Murder, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA) plotted and was directly involved in the
assassination of a Montenegrin presidential security advisor, a
Yugoslav cabinet minister said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Goran Matic told a news conference that
the CIA was directly involved in the assassination of Goran Zugic,
security adviser for Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
The assassination was conducted in Yugoslav territory in order
to destabilize the country and plunge it into chaos, Matic said.
</P>
<P>
The CIA also attempted to alienate Montenegro and Serbia, the
two republics forming Yugoslavia, he added.
</P>
<P>
A telephone conversation, reportedly recorded 20 minutes after
the assassination between two staff persons from U.S. agencies
based in Yugoslavia, was replayed at the news conference. One
person reportedly told another that "the task was successfully
executed 20 minutes ago."
</P>
<P>
Goran Zugic, 45, was murdered on May 31 in front of his home in
Podgorica, capital of Montenegro. He was the fourth highest-
ranking Yugoslav official murdered since the February killing of
Pavle Bulatovich, the federal defense minister, at a restaurant in
Belgrade. 
</P>
