<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Reduces Soil Erosion By 5,000 Sq. Km </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The province planted 280,000 hectares of trees and 80,000
hectares of grass since last winter. As a result, the improved
environment has helped reduce the amount of sand washed into the
rivers of the Yangtze and Yellow Rivers, China's two largest
rivers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the provincial government of Shaanxi adopted
measures to encourage farmers to turn farmland into forest and to
plant trees to increase vegetation coverage in its western regions.
</P>
<P>
By April, 2.1 million hectares of barren hills and land have
been contracted by farmers, enterprises, institutions and
individuals for afforestation. Some one million hectares of land
have been reclaimed thus far, involving a total investment of 460
million yuan (55.4 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The province aims to reclaim nearly 100,000 sq. km of soil
erosion in the next 12 years. The province had suffered from soil
erosion affecting 130,000 sq. km, or 60 percent of its land area.
Each year, 900 million tons of sand are washed into the Yangtze
and Yellow Rivers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
