<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Warns Against Violence in Papua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said the country could not afford to have a repeat of the
sort of violence that occurred in the province of Aceh over the
past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Rebels in Aceh, a province with the special autonomous status
in northwestern Sumatra, have been fighting for 25 years for
independence, a greater share of oil profits, and the right to
impose Islamic religious laws. More than 5,000 people have died in
the violence.
</P>
<P>
"We must not act like we did in the past. Our soldiers were
sent to Aceh and they attacked the people. It must not happen
again. Soldiers must be polite. I believe the people are not the
enemy," the president was quoted by the Indonesian Observer
Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said resorting to violence will only make matters worse.
He appealed to all parties including the Papuans to understand
each other so the problems will be resolved smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The Papua National Congress declared on Sunday that the
province will be no longer a part of the unitary state of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated his statement that the independence
movement does not represent the majority of people living in Papua,
so it won't receive support from the international community.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Commander of the Indonesian Defense Forces Admiral
Widodo A.S. said the military won't send additional troops to
Papua, despite the assertion by separatists that the province
independent.
</P>
<P>
"The number of personnel in Irian Jaya is adequate; therefore,
for the time being we will not send in additional troops," he said.
</P>
<P>
Irian Jaya Military Commander Major General Albert Inkiriwang
said the situation in the province is stable following the
congress.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that we can maintain such a condition," he said.
</P>
<P>
Inkiriwang said the military will take stern action if any
groups attempt to disturb security and order in the remote
province.
</P>
<P>
"We will see what happens. Security forces will take action if
necessary. But we will act in line with existing regulations," he
was quoted by the Indonesian Observer as saying. 
