<HEADLINE> Multi-ethnic Border Police Inaugurated in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia launched unified national
border police on Tuesday when 85 Muslim, Croat and Serb officers
began functioning at the Sarajevo international airport, the
Oslobodjenje newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The national border service will be made up of 3,000 members,
responsible for the security of the country's 1,665-kilometer
border line.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted U.N. special envoy to Bosnia Paul Klein as
saying that the national border service is crucial for fighting
against trafficking and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Smuggling and illegal importation have caused loss worth
several hundred million convertible marks, Klein said during the
inaugurating ceremony at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia's joint presidency described the border service in its
congratulatory message as a very important force in helping build
an integrated market for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The multi-ethnic police force is to replace two separate police
forces from Bosnia's post-war entities -- the Serb republic (
Republika Srpska) and the Muslim-Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Wolfgang Petritschan, high representative of
the Peace Implementation Council of Bosnia, Bosnia decided to
establish the joint police force in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
