<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Condemns KFOR for Wounding Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslavian government on
Tuesday made a strong protest regarding the United Nations'
mission in Kosovo and the international peacekeeping force KFOR
for wounding Serbian residents.
</P>
<P>
British troops in the KFOR shot and injured four Serbs,
including a child, in the village of Gracanica Tuesday, said
Stanimir Vukicevic, the chairman of the Yugoslav committee
cooperating with the UN mission in Kosovo (UNMIK).
</P>
<P>
Albanian extremists also wounded five Serbs in the village the
same day, with British troops on the scene, Vukicevic said in a
protest letter sent to the UN mission.
</P>
<P>
The actions of the peacekeeping forces show they are now
standing at the side of Albanian extremists, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 Serbs have been killed by Albanian extremists in the
past 10 days, Vukicevic said. He pointed out that the reasons for
the surge in anti-Serb attacks are because the UN mission and KFOR
have failed to implement the Security Council's resolution 1244
and disregard the violence of Albanian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Resolution 1244 ended NATO's 78-day bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia last June and set up the UNMIK. 
</P>
