<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferenc Madl Elected Hungary's New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Conservative academic Ferenc Madl
was elected Hungary's new president Tuesday in the third round of
voting after failing twice to secure enough support.
</P>
<P>
Madl, the 69-year-old sole candidate, was finally elected with
a simple majority of 243 votes out of 351 deputies present. He
failed to win the required two-thirds majority either in the first
round Monday or second earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hungarian Constitution, only a simple majority is
needed in the third round of voting.
</P>
<P>
He will be sworn in on August 4, succeeding President Arpad
Goencz, who has served the maximum two terms.
</P>
<P>
Madl was backed by the ruling conservative majority but also
enjoys support from the leftist and liberal opposition. Many
people were astonished at his failure to secure the post in the
first and second rounds of voting.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1931, Madl studied law in Budapest. He held ministerial
posts in Hungary's government between 1990 to 1994. In 1993, he
was elected into Hungary's Academy of Sciences as an academician .
</P>
</TEXT>
