<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCEAR General Assembly Report Focus on Chernobyl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Apart from an increase in thyroid
cancer, there is no evidence of a major health problem
attributable to radiation exposure as a result of the Chernobyl
incident, said a report approved by the United Nations Scientific
Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation (UNSCEAR) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There have been about 1,800 cases of thyroid cancer found in
children who were exposed at the time of the accident, and there
may be more such cases during the next decades, said UNSCEAR in
its 2000 report to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Apart from this increase, there is no additional scientific
evidence of a major public health problem due to radiation from
the nuclear accident, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The risk of leukemia, one of the main concerns due to its short
latency period, does not appear to be elevated, not even among
recovery operation workers, it said.
</P>
<P>
Although those individuals most exposed are at an increased
risk of radiation-associated effects, the great majority of the
Chernobyl population are not likely to experience serious health
consequences from exposure, the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
Chernobyl is the site of the world's worst nuclear accident. A
reactor caught fire and exploded in April 1986, spewing a cloud of
radioactive dust over Ukraine, Belarus, Russia and parts of
western Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government announced Monday that it will close
the Chernobyl power plant on December 15.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
