<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Tour de France Champion Pantani to Stand Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Tour de France champion Marco
Pantani was ordered on Tuesday to stand trial on charges of
sporting fraud in relation to high red blood cell levels recorded
in a 1995 race.
</P>
<P>
Investigating judge Stefano Celli ruled there were grounds to
send the Italian rider, who won both the Tour de France and the
Giro d'Italia in 1998, to trial.
</P>
<P>
Pantani was not in court in the northeastern town of Forli to
hear the decision, which related to a blood test in October 1995
during the Milan-Turin race in which his hematocrit (red blood
cell) level was found to be 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Riders are automatically suspended if they have red blood cell
counts of more than 50 percent. A high hematocrit reading can
indicate use of the banned performance-boosting substance
erythropoietin (EPO).
</P>
<P>
Pantani was originally sent to trial in April on the same
charge, even though public prosecuters had recommended the case be
shelved and the Italian Olympic Committee had decided to drop it
almost a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The April ruling was then reversed on a technicality before
being upheld again on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pantani, who helped his Mercatone Uno team mate Stefano
Garzelli to win this year's Giro and is looking forward to the
Tour in three weeks' time, was sensationally expelled from the
1999 Giro after failing a blood test.
</P>
<P>
With just two stages to race and victory within his reach, he
was found to have a hematocrit level of 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
Pantani walked away from the sport for almost a year but
returned at the eleventh hour to take his place on the starting
line of this year's Giro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
