<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan welcomed FIFA's decision to
bring forward the start of the 2002 World Cup by one day and said
it would not affect the country's preparations to co-host the
event.
</P>
<P>
FIFA's executive committee announced in Zurich on Tuesday that
the opening game would be held on May 31, making for a 31-day, 64-
match tournament.
</P>
<P>
Co-hosts Japan and South Korea had been working towards a June
1-June 30 World Cup and Japan had unveiled a two-year countdown
board on June 1.
</P>
<P>
Japanese organising committee chairman Sho Nasu said on Tuesday:
"From an operations point of view, this is a welcome development.
However, it has little effect on our preparations, and we will
continue with our work to welcome the world in 2002."
</P>
<P>
Under the FIFA plan, three games per day will be the norm.
</P>
<P>
The opening game is due to be held in Seoul, with the final at
Japan's Yokohama International Stadium on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Prices for the opening match in Seoul will range from $150 to $
500 while the final in Yokohama on June 30 will cost $300 to $750.
</P>
<P>
Fans will be able to buy up to four tickets per match.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said it anticipated that about three million tickets will
go on sale, with 50 percent going to the Japan and Korean
organising committees.
</P>
<P>
The remaining tickets would be sold internationally with 880,
000 going to the general public and participating national
associations.
</P>
<P>
Some 620,000 others would go to FIFA commercial affiliates and
rights holders, who in turn place a significant proportion of
their allocation at the disposal of the public through various
promotions, contests and lotteries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
