<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Hand Grenades Discovered on Campus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 16 hand grenades left over by
the Japanese army during World War II were recently discovered in
a middle school in Hegang city of northeastern China's
Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Police cordoned off the site after receiving report from the
school and later transported the grenades elsewhere to detonate.
</P>
<P>
Weaponry experts said the explosives were left over by the
Japanese army during the invasion of northeast China in the 1930s
and early 1940s. Although the grenades were buried underground for
decades and were covered in rust, they could still explode.
</P>
<P>
Police said that local residents have discovered more than 10,
000 bombs left over by the Japanese army in recent years in the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
