<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Century-Old Bridge Reopened To Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A renovation project has it possible
for a railway bridge built in 1909 to reopen to traffic recently
in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Built by the German, the 1,228-meter-long bridge spans the
Yellow River to the north of Jinan, capital of Shandong Province.
It was first opened to traffic in 1912 and was once the longest
bridge in Asia before the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was also once the section of a railway line linking
Tianjin and Nanjing. The bridge was closed in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Renovation of the bridge began in 1998 and ended in 1999. The
project cost more than 70 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The repaired bridge is now a part of the railway line running
from Jinan to Handan in neighboring Hebei Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
