<HEADLINE> Solomon Crisis Nearing End: Attempted Coup Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The crisis in the Solomon Islands
was on its way to resolution, Andrew Nori, who led the attempted
coup said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There has been intense negotiation within the last forty-eight
hours which has resulted in a formula being devised for the
resolution of the current political and security crisis," Nori
told the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) radio.
</P>
<P>
"The governor-general has now fixed a date for an urgent
meeting of parliament - that will be Thursday next week," Nori
said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu was no longer forced to
resign and could now freely move around the capital Honiara, Nori
said.
</P>
<P>
Ulufa'alu Tuesday night offered to resign as part of a deal to
end the country's crisis.
</P>
<P>
Solomon Islands' Minister of State Alfred Sasako had said after
an emergency cabinet meeting that Ulufa'alu "has given an
undertaking that if that was the price for the return of peace in
the Solomons, then, yes, he is willing to stand aside." 
</P>
</TEXT>
