<HEADLINE> Pistons Names George Irvine Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Detroit Pistons Tuesday
named George Irvine its coach and former star Joe Dumars it
president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Dumars announced that Brendan Suhr, formerly a top
assistant to Chuck Daly, will take over as director of player
personnel and Rick Sund will retain his role as general manager.
</P>
<P>
When Irvine replaced the fired Alvin Gentry on March 6, he made
the best of it, guiding the Pistons to a 14-10 record and a berth
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Irvine, 52, became an NBA head coach for the first time since a
20-game stint as the interim coach of Indiana in the 1988-89
season. He is a former ABA player who also has spent time as a
scout and an executive and has a career coaching mark of 68-140.
</P>
<P>
Dumars was a star guard for the Pistons for 14 seasons. He is
the team's all-time leader in regular-season games (1,018) and 3-
pointers (990) and helped lead Detroit to NBA titles in 1989 and
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
