<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Supports Education Institutions in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The "Socrates" program of the
European Union (EU) has been supporting since 1995 the improvement
of Romania's educational system by establishing direct contacts
between educational institutions in Romania and similar ones in
the EU countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a Wednesday report of the official Rompres news
agency, the EU sent in Romania in the past six years 19 million
euros only for solving some education-related problems such as the
change of the national education curriculum, descentralization of
the educational system, bringing the latest IT technologies in
universities, and transformation of the vocational schools.
</P>
<P>
Over 7,000 Romanian educational institutions benefited from the
EU's financial support. This year only, more than 2,000 Romanian
students study in Western universities on the basis of the "
Socrates" program. The study periods performed abroad are
recognized in Romania.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission decided this week to extend this
program, now called "Socrates II," until 2006 in 30 countries both
from Western and Eastern Europe. The total budget worth 1,885,000,
000 euros will allow an annual allocation worth 270 million euros.
</P>
<P>
The respective funds have been divided depending on the number
of citizens in each country. Romania will benefit as early of this
year by 8 million euros and next year other 18 million euros are
to be allotted.
</P>
<P>
The "Socrates II" program will be officially launched in
Romania on June 16 and will comprise several main destinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria: Eradicating Poverty, Improving Education and Health for Women Still Top Developing Countries' Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 7 (Xinhua )-- For developing countries
today, the quest for poverty eradication and improvement of
education and health for women and girls remains a top priority,
Nigeria said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Group of 77 and China at the United
Nations General Assembly special session on women, Aisha Ismail,
Minister for Women's Affairs and Youth Development of Nigeria,
said in pursuit of these goals, developing countries have reviewed
and strengthened policies and programs with a special focus on the
needs of women.
</P>
<P>
Since the Beijing Conference, the world has witnessed a lot of
radical transformation in the area of computer and information
technology and the one word that captures that transformation is
globalization, the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
While the benefits of globalization have been recognized, the
reality is that developing countries have been at a disadvantage,
the Minister noted.
</P>
<P>
More important for this conference, it must be acknowledged
that the negative impact of globalization is felt by women in
developing countries, and it is therefore, necessary to critically
examine how the issue of globalization is impacting on the
empowerment of women in the developing world, to enable the
development of appropriate programs and harness the opportunities
presented by this new trend, the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
A further impediment to the global commitment for gender
equality is the debt burden, and the painful implementation of
structural adjustment programs, which hang like millstones around
the necks of many countries in the developing world, she pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Despite the willingness and cooperation of some countries of
the developed world to relieve or cancel bilateral debt, and
through such measures as the Heavily Indebted poor Countries
Initiative, the debt burden of the developing world, particularly
in Africa, still remains very high, she said.
</P>
<P>
Certainly debt cancellation can release much needed vital
resources and enable developing countries to commerce the process
of rehabilitating the totally destroyed social sector, and freedom
from the debt burden will provide the means to positively impact
on the provision of basic social services to the people, the
Minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
