<HEADLINE> Colombian Teachers Support Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-five percent of the 300,000
Colombian state teachers supported the 48-hour strike called
Wednesday by the Colombian Educators Federation (FECODE), said the
leaders of that organization.
</P>
<P>
The strike that left without classes seven million students of
basic education and high schools, was called by the labor
organization to protest against a state plan. The teachers say
that the plan will cause the collapse of public education and will
promote privatization.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Gina Magnolia Riano said that her office will
inspect the schools where the classes were suspended and did not
dismiss the possibility that the strike will be declared illegal,
if regional governors ask for it.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, "The rights of the children prevail over
those of the teachers, and to take from them the right to
education is a very serious violation of the law."
</P>
<P>
FECODE president Gloria Ines Ramirez explained that the strike
was called to protest against a series of courses the teachers
must attend during their mid-year vacation, which reduce the
resting time for the FECODE members.
</P>
<P>
The FECODE said that the reforms the government is promoting in
education are part of "impositions" of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to the Colombian government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
