<HEADLINE> Group of Rio Demands New Financial Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Rio will demand
from the rich countries a new architecture for the international
financial system, Honduran Foreign Minister Roberto Flores said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This position is contained in a declaration made at the end of
the group's 14th Summit Meeting, scheduled for June 15-16 in
Cartagena, Colombia, said Flores, according to reports from
Tegucigalpa, the Honduras capital.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be attended by the presidents of Guatemala, El
Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Panama, Mexico,
Colombia, Venezuela, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Bolivia, Chile,
Paraguay, Uruguay, Argentina and the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
Guyana Prime Minister Samuel Hinds will attend the summit on
behalf of the Caribbean countries. The Group of Rio is the most
important mechanism of political coordination of Latin America and
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
"The design of a new architecture for the international
financial system will be one of the themes to be discussed at the
summit, because of the concern existing in Latin America about the
way the financial markets instability is affecting our economies,"
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
There is a consensus in the Group of Rio for a stable financial
system with elements that will avoid and prevent crises, added
Flores.
</P>
<P>
The text drafted in preparatory meetings says that Latin
America will call on the developed countries for a dialogue in the
appropriated forums for the design of a new financial architecture
that will reduce the destabilizing risks and effects produced by
volatility.
</P>
<P>
The region sees with worries the possibility of a worsening
financial crisis that would imperil the structural economic
reforms started in the last decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
