<HEADLINE> Rains in Guatemala Leave 21 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The situation forced President Alfonso Portillo to declare a "
state of public calamity" in all the country for 30 days ,
according to reports reaching here from Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
National Disasters Reduction Coordinating (CONRED) agency
sources explained Wednesday that 21 persons have died and three
were injured since the start of the rains at the beginning of May.
</P>
<P>
CONRED said that 2,143 people have been affected by the rains,
and 505 of them have been evacuated to safer places, while other
551 are still in a situation of peril
</P>
<P>
The rains have also destroyed 68 houses and damaged 388, and 98
more are in risk of collapsing, added the same source.
</P>
<P>
President Portillo decreed Tuesday the "state of public
calamity" and decided to concentrate all the forces of the
government to address the situation.
</P>
<P>
Meteorology Institute sources said that the rain has surpassed
this year by one hundred percent the recordings of the last
decades.  
