<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Meaningful Talks on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council looked forward to the talks, it said
in a press statement issued after hearing a briefing by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special adviser for Cyprus Alvaro
de Soto Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Council members welcomed the fact that the first two rounds of
talks had been conducted in a positive and constructive atmosphere,
and without preconditions," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"They commended the commitment shown by the participants, and
encouraged all concerned to continue their efforts towards a
comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus question on the basis of
the relevant resolutions of the Security Council," it added.
</P>
<P>
The Council promised to take early action to renew the mandate
of the U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus by six months until
December 15.
</P>
<P>
The third round of talks, originally scheduled for May 23, was
postponed due to President Glafcos Clerides' colon surgery.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an eastern Mediterranean island country, has been
divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north and the Greek
Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive pro-Athens military coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has tried to reunite the island but talks
between the two communities have produced no tangible results.
</P>
<P>
Under a renewed call from Annan, the two sides held two rounds
of talks, first in New York last December and then in Geneva early
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side has maintained that the only way out of the
issue is to establish a confederation on the basis of two states,
an idea rejected by the Greek state and the international
community at large.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, which follows the matter "with the
closest of interest," hopes that the proximity talks will prepare
the ground for meaningful negotiations leading to a comprehensive
settlement, it said Wednesday, noting that "the status quo in
Cyprus is unacceptable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000607.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Land Crisis not to Spill Over to S. Africa: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki Wednesday dismissed jitters that land occupation by blacks
would happen in his country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the occupation of white-owned farms by war
veterans in Zimbabwe where at least 30 people have been killed
since the crisis began in February, Mbeki said his government
would not allow the same situation to happen in his country.
</P>
<P>
There is no need to worry that a violent claim for land
restitution could happen in South Africa, where the transition
from apartheid to democracy has largely been peaceful since the
1994 all-race elections ended the system of minority white rule,
the president said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no basis to assume that what is happening in Zimbabwe
must necessarily happen in South Africa," he stressed, assuring
that "there will be no spillover in South Africa." 
</P>
</TEXT>
