<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 7 (Xinhua) -- An accord aimed at boosting bilateral
cultural, scientific and technological cooperation between Italy
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) was signed here
Wednesday between the two parties, the Italian Foreign Ministry
said in a communique.
</P>
<P>
The accord, signed by Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
and Palestinian International Cooperation Minister Nabil Shaath,
specifically targets increased collaboration between universities
and resources such as archives and libraries.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry also said that the evaluation and research
of archaeological sites and cultural patrimonies, as well as
exchanges between experts, researchers and training ventures, were
high up on the list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
The accord also stipulates the establishment of linguistic,
cultural and teacher exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The accord reinforces past and existing Italo-Palestinian
exchanges, such as a project started three years ago by the
Italian Consulate in Jerusalem, which brought Italian language
courses to the Bir Zeit University, as well as current
negotiations to transmit Italian television programs on
Palestinian networks.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry communique stressed the success of past
joint archaeological projects, such as an Italo-Palestinian dig in
Tell es-Sultan (the Biblical Jericho) organized by Rome's La
Sapienza University and the Palestinian Ministry for Tourism and
Antiquities.
</P>
<P>
The Jericho dig, the communique read, opened opportunities for
researchers to explore the site, study the urban and social
structures of the ancient town, evaluate its potential for the
tourist industry and train future archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the two ministers discussed the Middle
East peace process, and Dini said he hoped peace would be
established as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
Shaath said that the cultural cooperation accord would help
boost dialogue between Italy and the Palestinian territories, and
thanked the Italian government for the support it has lent to the
PNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
