<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy-Spain Summit Aims to Boost Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Premier Jose Maria Aznar will
arrive in Italy's Naples Friday for the annual two-day summit
between Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
The summit aims to reinforce the two countries' cooperation in
the Mediterranean, the European Union and on the world stage, the
Italian Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A sign of the importance Aznar attaches to the event is the
fact that he is bringing, at his request, not three ministers as
at previous summits, but five.
</P>
<P>
After his dazzling election win, this will be the first
international outing for the second Aznar administration and he
will be keen to put on a good show.
</P>
<P>
Topping the agenda of the bilateral talks will be the fight
against organized crime, which was not originally slated.
</P>
<P>
Italy is expected to address the problem of the hundreds of
Italian Mafiosi and other criminals who, according to Italian
prosecutors and judges, are prevented from being extradited
because of fine legal distinctions.
</P>
<P>
Italian sources cited by the Madrid daily El Pais say there are
over 1,000 Italian criminals, including most wanted Mafiosi, who
have found a "golden refuge" in Spain.
</P>
<P>
But Madrid judicial sources have claimed the numbers are much
lower and the reason for extradition refusals is the lack of
guarantee that the criminals will receive a fresh trial in Italy.
</P>
<P>
On Europe, the two countries have similar positions on the
Intergovernmental Conference, enlargement, the euro, and Balkan
policy, Italian diplomats say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
