<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Condemns "Terrorist Bombing" in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
condemned a bombing that took place earlier in the day and killed
at least 21 people in Sri Lanka, saying it was a "barbarous
terrorist bombing."
</P>
<P>
"The United States strongly supports the territorial integrity
of Sri Lanka and a political solution to the conflict that would
provide dignity and security for all Sri Lankans. But again, we
strongly condemn today's barbarous terrorist bombing there," said
State Department spokesman Philip Reeker at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The bombing happened as a man strapped with explosives to his
body attacked a group of people, including Industrial Development
Minister C.V. Gooneratne who was killed on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Reeker said this was terrorist method which "has been used
frequently in the past by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam."
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka police said the attacker was a "Black Tiger," a
suicide bomber with the separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
