<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks Continue To Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- All European leading stock markets
ended lower Wednesday as media-related issues slumped and telecom
stocks came under pressure ahead of U.S. data and an expected ECB
rate hike.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 suffered its second downturn in three session
as technology stocks weakened and the market overall lost impetus
after last week's advance to nine week highs.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index fell 43 points, or 0.7 percent, to 6,503.8
with computer-services firm Logica plunging 11 percent after its
earnings forecast disappointed investors.
</P>
<P>
Outside of the FTSE 100, shares of electronics and computer-
based equipment Feedback sand 22.4 percent after warning that its
full-year profits would not meet market expectations.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300 index, a basket of Europe's biggest
companies, shed 0.5 percent to 1,616.89. The media sector sub-
index fell 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronically traded Xetra Dax was down 66.
82 points, or 0.91 percent, at 7,292.98, with index heavyweight
Deutsche Telekom down 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Worries about the higher-than-expected cost of French UMTS
mobile phone licenses and a sluggish Nasdaq forced the Paris
Bourse to close lower for the third straight day. The CAC 40 index
ended down 91.27 or 1.39 percent at 6,498.5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
